export const FRAMEWORKS_BLOCKS: ReadonlyArray<{ id: string; content: string }> = [
  { id: "adr", content: "# Framework: Context → Options → Decision → Consequences (ADR)\n\nArchitecture Decision Records. A four-node framework for explaining a decision where **the alternatives matter** — where the listener needs to know not only what you chose but what you considered and rejected.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Design reviews (you need to show the decision was deliberate, not arbitrary)\n- Post-mortems with forks (we could have done X, we chose Y, here's why)\n- RFC presentations\n- Any moment someone might ask \"why didn't you just…?\"\n- Technical decisions being explained to someone who will *also* have opinions\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Context** — the problem and the constraints operating on it. Same as CDI's Context node, but usually slightly longer because the options need the same constraints to be understandable.\n2. **Options** — the alternatives you considered. At least two, ideally three. Each option gets a one-line tradeoff, not a paragraph. This is the distinguishing feature of ADR: you *name* the rejects, not just the winner.\n3. **Decision** — the option you picked, stated plainly.\n4. **Consequences** — what you accept and what you give up. Same as CDI's Impact node. This is the honesty check — a mature ADR names the real cost, not just the benefit.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Strong:**\n> \"[Context] We needed real-time leaderboard updates for the validation feature, with expected peak load of 5K concurrent users and a 50-rep history per user. [Options] Three realistic options. First, a Postgres-only approach — simple but doesn't scale past ~1K concurrent. Second, Postgres + Redis sorted sets — moderate complexity, scales well, but adds a second data store to operate. Third, managed service like Liveblocks — zero ops, but $600/mo and a vendor lock. [Decision] We went with Postgres + Redis sorted sets. [Consequences] We get horizontal scale and keep cost flat, at the price of operating Redis and maintaining two sources of truth that we reconcile on write.\"\n\n## Why ADRs exist\n\nMichael Nygard introduced ADRs in 2011 in a Thoughtworks post titled \"Documenting Architecture Decisions,\" arguing that undocumented decisions become archaeological puzzles six months later. The ADR format was designed for written docs but translates cleanly to live verbal delivery — with the constraint that the **Options** section must be fast, not exhaustive.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Options bloat** — spending 60 seconds per option in live delivery. Each option gets one sentence. If it needs more, you should be writing a doc, not speaking.\n- **No real alternatives** — listing two options where one is obviously bad just to make the chosen one look good. The audience will notice and you'll lose trust. Every option listed should be a genuine candidate.\n- **Missing Consequences** — listing the decision without the tradeoffs. Same failure as CDI.\n- **Passive-voice decision** — \"and we ended up going with Redis\" weakens the commitment. \"We chose Redis\" is the right tone.\n- **Defending the rejects** — re-relitigating why option 2 lost. The Options section is a snapshot, not a debate.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"Well, there were a lot of options, so…\"\n- \"I mean, we could have done anything, but…\"\n- \"We kind of just went with Redis because…\"\n- Listing six options in live delivery (write a doc)\n\n## ADR vs CDI\n\nUse **CDI** (`cdi.md`) when the alternatives are either obvious or uninteresting — three nodes, faster, cleaner.\n\nUse **ADR** when at least one of these is true:\n- The audience will ask \"why not X?\" if X isn't named\n- The rejected options are themselves a signal of rigor\n- The decision will be reviewed later and the alternatives need to be on record\n\n## Origin\n\nMichael Nygard, \"Documenting Architecture Decisions\" (2011), Thoughtworks. Originally a written-doc format; adopted widely in engineering orgs and adapted for verbal delivery in design reviews. Gained traction through tools like `adr-tools` and the `docs/adr/` convention in open-source repos.\n\n## See also\n\n- `cdi.md` — the three-node short form when alternatives don't matter\n- `cei.md` — Claim → Evidence → Implication, for contested decisions\n- `bluf.md` — if the alternatives don't fit in the time you have\n" },
  { id: "aida", content: "# Framework: Attention → Interest → Desire → Action (AIDA)\n\nThe oldest persuasion framework still in wide use. Elias St. Elmo Lewis, 1898. Designed for audiences who don't yet know they have a problem and won't read a second sentence unless the first one earned it.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Cold audiences — people who didn't come to listen to you\n- Opening talks at conferences\n- Marketing copy and landing pages\n- Any moment you have to *earn* attention before you have trust\n- Pitch openers where the listener's default is to tune out\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Attention** — the hook that makes them stop. A surprising statistic, a personal story opener, a physical demo, a provocative question. 5–15 seconds.\n2. **Interest** — the reason they should keep listening. Why this matters to them, specifically. 15–30 seconds.\n3. **Desire** — why they'd want this to be true *for them*. The emotional / aspirational pull. 30–60 seconds.\n4. **Action** — the specific thing you want them to do next. One move, clearly named.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Strong (conference opener):**\n> \"In the next 60 seconds, three people in this room will decide what to wear tomorrow and forget every slide I'm about to show you. [**Attention**] That's not because what I'm going to say isn't important — it's because the human brain is literally designed to forget structured information within hours unless it's attached to a story. [**Interest**] Imagine you're running a sales team where every rep remembers the framework you taught them six months later, not because they wrote it down, but because it's muscle memory. [**Desire**] I'm going to spend the next 10 minutes showing you exactly how we built that, and I'll send everyone in this room the framework if you put your business card in the box by the door. [**Action**]\"\n\n## Why Attention is the hardest node\n\nBy far the most common failure in AIDA is spending 90% of your effort on Interest and Desire and treating Attention as a throwaway greeting. But if Attention fails, the rest of the framework never runs — the listener already tuned out.\n\nGreat Attention hooks are **specific**, **unexpected**, and **relevant in under 10 seconds**. Vague, expected, or abstract openings lose the listener before you've said anything worth hearing.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Greeting as Attention** — \"Hi, I'm excited to be here today\" is not an attention hook\n- **Attention without Interest bridge** — the hook lands but doesn't connect to anything the audience cares about\n- **Skipping to Action** — asking for the commitment before building Desire\n- **Interest that's about you, not them** — \"let me tell you about our amazing team\" instead of \"here's why this matters for you\"\n- **Desire that's generic** — \"imagine a better future\" instead of \"imagine your CFO thanking you for cutting $400K from the training budget\"\n- **Vague Action** — \"reach out if you're interested\" is not an action\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"Thanks for having me, it's great to be here today…\"\n- \"Before we get started, a little about me…\"\n- \"Today we're going to be talking about…\"\n- \"Let me show you our platform…\"\n- \"Feel free to reach out if you'd like to learn more…\"\n\n## AIDA vs modern alternatives\n\nAIDA is designed for *cold* audiences. For warm audiences — people who asked for the meeting — use:\n\n- **Minto Pyramid** (`minto.md`) when the listener already wants the answer\n- **SCQA** (`scqa.md`) when the listener knows the area but doesn't yet feel the tension\n- **PSPA** (`pspa.md`) when the listener is already engaged and you're making a specific ask\n\nAIDA remains useful in 2026 for its original purpose: situations where you have to *win* the listener's attention before you can inform, persuade, or ask.\n\n## Origin\n\nElias St. Elmo Lewis, advertising pioneer, 1898. Originally formulated for print advertising but has been adapted into sales, speech, copywriting, and presentation methodology continuously for 128 years. The durability comes from the fact that attention is still the first constraint in any form of communication — and probably always will be.\n\n## See also\n\n- `pspa.md` — for problem-centric sales framing once attention is earned\n- `scqa.md` — for building tension before delivering the answer to warm audiences\n- `storytelling.md` — the domain MD for public-speaking and narrative craft\n" },
  { id: "bie", content: "# Framework: Behavior → Impact → Expectation (BIE)\n\nA feedback framework for delivering tough-but-kind corrective conversations. Derived from the **SBI** (Situation–Behavior–Impact) model developed at the **Center for Creative Leadership** in the 1990s, extended with an explicit forward-looking Expectation node.\n\n## When to use\n\n- 1:1 performance conversations\n- Calling out a specific behavior a teammate exhibited\n- Any feedback moment where you need the other person to hear it without getting defensive\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Behavior** — the specific observed behavior. Concrete. No interpretation. No character judgment. \"In Wednesday's standup you interrupted Priya twice\" — not \"you're being dismissive lately.\"\n2. **Impact** — the effect that behavior had on the work, the team, or the outcome. Factual, not emotional. \"Priya stopped contributing for the rest of the meeting, and we didn't hear the caching concern until after the decision was made.\"\n3. **Expectation** — what you need to happen going forward. Specific, measurable, non-negotiable. \"Going forward, I need you to let whoever is speaking finish before you respond, even if you disagree.\"\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n> \"In Wednesday's standup, you interrupted Priya twice while she was explaining the cache issue. [**Behavior**] She stopped contributing for the rest of the meeting, and we didn't hear her point until after the decision was made — which we've now had to reopen. [**Impact**] Going forward, I need you to let whoever is speaking finish before you respond, even when you disagree. [**Expectation**]\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Generalizing the behavior** — \"you interrupt people a lot\" instead of \"in Wednesday's standup at 9:45\". Specificity is what keeps it from feeling like character assassination.\n- **Interpreting instead of observing** — \"you were being dismissive\" is an interpretation; \"you cut her off twice\" is the behavior. Stay on the observable side.\n- **Softening the impact** — \"it was kind of awkward\" loses the signal. Name the concrete cost.\n- **Vague expectation** — \"try to be more considerate\" is unmeasurable. The Expectation node needs to be a specific, checkable future behavior.\n- **Opening with Impact** — \"you really hurt Priya's feelings…\" puts the listener on the defensive before they know why. Always lead with Behavior.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"I just wanted to say…\"\n- \"This isn't a big deal, but…\"\n- \"You always…\" / \"You never…\"\n- Sandwich feedback (praise → criticism → praise) — well-researched as counterproductive; receivers discount the praise and miss the criticism\n\n## Origin\n\nCenter for Creative Leadership, Situation-Behavior-Impact (SBI) model, 1990s. Researched at CCL and Harvard. The Expectation extension is widely used in modern management coaching (Kim Scott, *Radical Candor*; Stone & Heen, *Thanks for the Feedback*).\n\n## See also\n\n- `wsw.md` — What → So What → Now What for retrospectives, where the reflection is collaborative rather than corrective\n" },
  { id: "bluf", content: "# Framework: Bottom Line → Context → Next Step (BLUF)\n\nRuthless compression. Originally US military communication doctrine, now standard in exec email subject lines and live 60-second updates. Use when you have less time than you'd like and the listener has less patience than you'd hope.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Emails to executives (subject line + first sentence)\n- 60-second hallway updates\n- Status updates in a meeting you're not on the agenda for\n- Slack messages to a VP\n- Any moment the listener will re-read this later in a hurry\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Bottom Line** — the one sentence they need to hear. If they read only this sentence, they know what they need to do.\n2. **Context** — the minimum background to make the bottom line make sense. One sentence, two at the most.\n3. **Next Step** — what you need from them, or what happens next.\n\n## Exemplar phrasings\n\n**Slack to a VP:**\n> \"**Bottom line:** the migration is going to slip two weeks. **Context:** the data validation step is uncovering corruption we didn't see in staging. **Next step:** I need you to push the investor demo from the 18th to the 25th. I can draft the note to the board if you want.\"\n\n**Email subject + opening:**\n> **Subject:** Migration slipping 2 weeks — need board date pushed\n>\n> Data validation is uncovering corruption we didn't catch in staging, so the migration will land the 25th instead of the 11th. I need the board demo pushed to match. Draft note attached for your review.\n\n## Why BLUF works\n\nExecutives scan. They read subject lines, opening sentences, and Ctrl-F for their name. BLUF is engineered to survive that reading pattern: every key piece of information is where a scanning reader would find it.\n\nBLUF also **protects the sender** — you can't be accused of \"burying the bad news\" if the bad news is in sentence one.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Throat-clearing opener** — \"Hi [Name], hope you're doing well. Just wanted to share a quick update on…\" — BLUF has no greeting-as-preamble. The bottom line comes first.\n- **Vague bottom line** — \"There's been some movement on the migration project\" is not a bottom line. *\"Migration slipping two weeks\"* is.\n- **Next step missing** — ending at Context. If BLUF doesn't tell the reader what to do with the information, it's just a status report.\n- **Over-contextualizing** — when Context runs longer than Bottom Line + Next Step combined, the shape is broken. Cut the context in half.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"I just wanted to give you a quick heads up on something…\"\n- \"I know you're busy so I'll make this quick, but…\"\n- \"Long story short…\" (then tells the long story)\n- \"Before I get into the details…\"\n\n## BLUF vs Minto vs SCQA\n\n- **BLUF** when you have ≤ 60 seconds or ≤ 3 sentences — maximum compression, minimum structure\n- **Minto** when you have 2–5 minutes — Answer + three Reasons, full drill-in on request\n- **SCQA** when the listener doesn't yet feel the tension and you need them to want the answer\n\n## Origin\n\nUS military communication doctrine. The term \"Bottom Line Up Front\" dates to military intelligence briefings in the mid-20th century, designed for commanders who read only the first paragraph of any report and act on it. Adopted by management consulting in the 1990s and mainstreamed into exec email norms by the 2000s.\n\n## See also\n\n- `minto.md` — when you have room for Reasons\n- `scqa.md` — when the listener needs tension before the answer\n- `cdi.md` — when the bottom line is a decision that needs justification\n" },
  { id: "cdi", content: "# Framework: Context → Decision → Impact (CDI)\n\nA three-node framework for explaining a technical or strategic decision to any audience — especially one that was not in the room when the decision was made.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Design reviews\n- Post-mortems\n- Explaining an engineering decision to non-technical stakeholders\n- Status updates where a choice needs to feel understandable, not arbitrary\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Context** — the background the listener needs before the decision makes sense. Short. Just enough that \"we chose X\" lands.\n2. **Decision** — the choice, stated plainly. No hedging, no \"we sort of went with\", no \"eventually decided\". One sentence.\n3. **Impact** — the honest consequences and tradeoffs. What you gain *and* what you give up. This is what separates a mature CDI rep from a defensive one.\n\n## Exemplar phrasings\n\n**Strong:**\n> \"Our p99 latency was hitting 800ms on the checkout path during peak, which broke our SLA. We moved checkout to a dedicated read replica. That cuts p99 under 200ms, at the cost of 30 seconds of replication lag on inventory counts — acceptable because we already reconcile at the payment step.\"\n\n**Template:**\n> \"[Context: specific problem with numbers]. We decided to [Decision: the specific choice]. That means [Impact: specific gain] at the cost of [Impact: honest tradeoff].\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Context bloat** — 90 seconds of background for a 30-second decision. Cut the context in half.\n- **Hedging the decision** — \"we sort of decided…\", \"we ended up going with…\". Say it plainly: *\"We chose X.\"*\n- **Skipping Impact** — ending at the decision. Listeners will ask \"…and?\" in their heads. Without Impact, the framework is incomplete.\n- **Defensive Impact** — hiding the tradeoff to avoid criticism. This loses trust. Honest tradeoffs build it.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- Opening with \"So basically what we did was…\"\n- Leading with the tradeoff before stating the decision\n- Listing every alternative you considered (that's ADR, not CDI)\n\n## Origin\n\nDerived from Architecture Decision Records (ADRs) as popularized by Michael Nygard (2011), simplified to three nodes for live verbal delivery.\n\n## See also\n\n- `adr.md` — the 4-node version (Context → Options → Decision → Consequences) when alternatives matter\n- `bluf.md` — when you have under 60 seconds and need maximum compression\n" },
  { id: "cei", content: "# Framework: Claim → Evidence → Implication (CEI)\n\nThe backbone of any argument that could be challenged. Adapted from classical Aristotelian logos for modern business communication. Use CEI when you expect pushback, when the claim is contested, or when the listener will reasonably ask \"why should I believe you?\"\n\n## When to use\n\n- Debates and defenses of a recommendation\n- Persuasive presentations where the audience starts skeptical\n- Performance review self-assessments (\"here's what I did and why it mattered\")\n- Any moment your claim needs to survive being questioned\n- Academic, legal, or scientific argumentation in business form\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Claim** — the assertion you're making. Clear, falsifiable, worth defending. Not a question, not a hedge.\n2. **Evidence** — data, reasoning, or a specific example that supports the claim. Real. Cited. Checkable.\n3. **Implication** — why the claim *matters* to your audience specifically. This is the \"so what\" that converts logic into commitment.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Strong:**\n> \"Our scoring pipeline's trend lines are more defensible than any competitor's. [**Claim**] Because we run deterministic signal extraction on conciseness, thinking-on-the-spot, and handling-pressure, three of our six dimensions are mathematically stable — same input returns the same score today, next week, and after every model release. Yoodli, Speeko, and Orai all run pure-LLM scoring, which means their numbers drift with every model update. We tested this by re-scoring the same audio clip across three weeks and found our composite moved by less than 0.5 points; theirs moved by 7-12. [**Evidence**] That matters because enterprise L&D buyers need to report measurable improvement to their CFO, and drifting numbers get caught in audit. Our defensibility is the difference between a pilot that converts and a pilot that gets killed in month four. [**Implication**]\"\n\n## Why Implication is load-bearing\n\nCEI distinguishes itself from similar frameworks because of the *Implication* node. Most argument frameworks stop at evidence and assume the audience will infer the importance. They won't — they'll be too busy evaluating whether the evidence is strong enough. The Implication is where you close the loop: \"here's what this fact *means* to you, specifically.\"\n\nWithout Implication, CEI collapses into a fact statement. With it, CEI becomes an argument.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Vague Claim** — \"I think we should probably consider X\" is not a claim; it's a hedge. The claim must be stake-worthy.\n- **Weak Evidence** — \"from what I've seen\" or \"I've heard that…\" is not evidence; it's memory. Cite specifics.\n- **Too much Evidence** — drowning the claim in six data points when one or two land harder\n- **Missing Implication** — ending at Evidence and leaving the listener to draw the conclusion\n- **Circular Evidence** — \"it works because it works\" or \"our users love it because they use it\"\n- **Evidence that doesn't match the Claim** — a common failure mode where the data supports a related but different claim\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"I kind of think maybe…\"\n- \"It seems like…\"\n- \"A lot of people believe…\"\n- \"Studies show…\" (without the study)\n- \"Obviously…\" (if it were obvious, you wouldn't need CEI)\n- Presenting Evidence first and building to the Claim — that's a different structure entirely\n\n## CEI vs Minto\n\nUse **Minto** (`minto.md`) when the audience is *ready* to hear your answer and you just need to justify it. Three reasons, on-deck evidence.\n\nUse **CEI** when the audience will *contest* your answer and you need each claim to be individually defended. CEI is Minto hardened for debate — single claim, heavy evidence, explicit implication.\n\nIn a long-form argument, use both: Minto for the overall structure, CEI for each individual sub-claim that might be attacked.\n\n## Origin\n\nClassical rhetoric, specifically Aristotle's concept of *logos* — argument from logic and evidence. Formalized into modern debate curriculum in the 20th century (cross-examination debate, policy debate). Adapted for business communication in the 1990s as part of structured-argumentation training at firms like McKinsey, BCG, and Bain.\n\n## See also\n\n- `minto.md` — Answer → Reasons → Evidence, for uncontested audiences\n- `scqa.md` — Situation → Complication → Question → Answer, for when the problem itself needs to be established first\n- `structure.md` — the skill dimension most stressed by CEI\n" },
  { id: "fab", content: "# Framework: Feature → Advantage → Benefit (FAB)\n\nClassic sales framework. Translates \"what the thing does\" into \"why the buyer should care.\" The simplest way to move from mechanics to meaning in a product pitch.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Product demos (especially feature walkthroughs)\n- Explaining a technical capability to a non-technical buyer\n- Answering \"what does your product do?\" in 20 seconds\n- Any moment you're describing a capability and need the listener to *feel* the value, not just understand the mechanism\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Feature** — what the thing actually is. The mechanic. *\"Cognify generates a framework for every scenario.\"*\n2. **Advantage** — what it does *better* than the alternative. The comparison. *\"Unlike a static script, the framework adapts to the audience and constraints the user types in.\"*\n3. **Benefit** — what it *means* for the buyer's life or work. The outcome. *\"So an AE walking into a real call already has a structured way to think about it, not a memorized script that breaks the moment the customer goes off-topic.\"*\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Strong:**\n> \"[Feature] Cognify's scoring pipeline runs deterministic signal extraction on every rep — filler rate, pacing, pauses — alongside the LLM layer. [Advantage] That means our trend lines are stable across time in a way Yoodli's and Speeko's aren't — re-scoring yesterday's audio returns the same number today. [Benefit] Your L&D team can report real improvement to the CFO with numbers that hold up under audit, not vibes that drift every release.\"\n\n## Why the Benefit node is load-bearing\n\nMost salespeople stop at Advantage. They describe what's better and assume the buyer will infer the \"so what?\" They don't. The Benefit node is the buyer's *so what*, translated into their language, their KPI, their boss's question. Without Benefit, the buyer hears \"this is technically interesting\" and forgets.\n\nThe Benefit also has to match the specific buyer's world. \"Saves time\" is not a benefit — \"cuts your monthly calibration review from 4 hours to 30 minutes\" is. The Benefit is concrete or it's nothing.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Feature dumping** — listing 6 features without connecting to Advantage or Benefit\n- **Advantage without Benefit** — \"it's faster / better / more accurate\" without the \"which means for you…\"\n- **Generic Benefit** — \"saves time\", \"drives efficiency\", \"improves outcomes\" — these are not benefits, they are the *category* of benefits\n- **Buyer-mismatched Benefit** — describing the benefit to the engineer when you're pitching the CFO\n- **Feature dressed as Benefit** — \"the benefit is that you get our AI-powered platform\" — that's still a feature\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"It comes with…\"\n- \"It's powered by…\"\n- \"It's best-in-class at…\"\n- \"The main differentiator is…\" (then describes a feature)\n- Bullet-list delivery (\"First, it does X. Second, it does Y. Third, it does Z.\")\n\n## FAB vs PSPA\n\nUse **FAB** when the buyer has already agreed there's a problem and you're now showing the product's mechanics. FAB is *feature-centric*.\n\nUse **PSPA** (`pspa.md`) when the buyer doesn't yet agree there's a problem, or when you're opening the conversation. PSPA is *problem-centric*.\n\nIn a full sales cycle: PSPA runs the discovery and pitch; FAB runs the demo and feature drill-down.\n\n## Origin\n\nAttributed to Xerox PARC's sales training programs in the 1960s, later systematized by Dale Carnegie Training and mainstreamed into enterprise sales curricula by the 1980s. FAB is the *oldest* modern sales framework still in wide use — older than SPIN (Rackham, 1988) and older than the Challenger Sale (Dixon, 2011).\n\n## See also\n\n- `pspa.md` — Problem → Solution → Proof → Ask, for problem-centric framing\n- `aida.md` — Attention → Interest → Desire → Action, for cold-audience persuasion\n- `cdi.md` — Context → Decision → Impact, for technical-decision framing\n" },
  { id: "minto", content: "# Framework: Answer → Reasons → Evidence (Minto Pyramid)\n\nThe short-form variant of Barbara Minto's Pyramid Principle. Lead with the answer, then justify it. The opposite of SCQA — use Minto when **urgency beats tension**, when the audience wants the punchline *now* and will drill in on demand.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Executive emails (\"what did we decide and why?\")\n- The first 30 seconds of any senior meeting\n- Status updates to a busy stakeholder\n- Any moment the listener will interrupt you if you take too long to land the point\n- Live Q&A under pressure\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Answer** — your conclusion. No preamble, no lead-up, no \"so the way I see it…\". One sentence. The top of the pyramid.\n2. **Reasons** — three supporting reasons, mutually exclusive. Not a list of everything you considered — the three that *earn* the answer.\n3. **Evidence** — the data, logic, or example behind each reason. Only delivered if the listener drills in. In written form, Evidence lives in the paragraph under each reason. In spoken form, it lives in your head, ready to deploy.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Strong:**\n> \"We should sunset the mobile app and push web-first. [**Answer**] Three reasons. First, our mobile install base has declined 40% year over year. Second, the engineering cost of maintaining two codebases is consuming 30% of our frontend capacity. Third, our web conversion has now overtaken mobile on every metric we track. [**Reasons**] Happy to go deeper on any of those. [**Evidence on deck**]\"\n\n## Why three\n\nThree is not arbitrary. Two reasons feels thin and hedgeable. Four or more and the listener stops tracking. The Heath Brothers (Made to Stick) and Minto both land on three as the cognitive sweet spot for structured reasoning under time pressure.\n\nThe three reasons must be **mutually exclusive** — if two reasons overlap, they collapse into one and the structure falls apart. \"Cost, speed, and efficiency\" is two reasons at most (speed and efficiency overlap).\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Burying the answer** — \"so there are a few things to consider, and I've been thinking about this…\" *That's not Minto.* Minto opens with the answer.\n- **Three overlapping reasons** — fails the mutually-exclusive test. Collapse them into distinct ones.\n- **Evidence-first delivery** — starting with the data and building to the answer. That's the opposite of Minto. In exec communication, the listener has already decided whether to keep listening by the time you finish the data.\n- **More than three reasons** — attention breaks. Pick the three strongest and cut the rest.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"Well, there are several factors at play here…\"\n- \"Let me give you some context first…\"\n- \"I've been thinking about this a lot and I think…\"\n- Ending without offering the Evidence on deck\n\n## When NOT to use Minto\n\nUse **SCQA** (`scqa.md`) when the audience doesn't yet feel the tension — when you need them to *want* the answer before you give it. Minto assumes the listener already wants the answer and just needs it delivered.\n\nUse **BLUF** (`bluf.md`) when you have under 60 seconds and three reasons won't fit.\n\n## Origin\n\nBarbara Minto, *The Pyramid Principle: Logic in Writing and Thinking* (1987). Minto was McKinsey's first woman consultant and built the pyramid principle during the 1960s while training new consultants to write client memos. The Answer-first form became McKinsey's house style and spread through consulting into exec comms broadly.\n\n## See also\n\n- `scqa.md` — Situation → Complication → Question → Answer, for when tension earns the answer\n- `bluf.md` — Bottom Line → Context → Next Step, even tighter compression\n- `cei.md` — Claim → Evidence → Implication, for when the claim will be contested\n" },
  { id: "ppf", content: "# Framework: Past → Present → Future (PPF)\n\nThe classic narrative structure for self-introductions and career framing. The default framework for \"tell me about yourself\" and the cleanest way to make a personal story feel structured without feeling rehearsed.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Interview openers (\"tell me about yourself\")\n- Self-introductions in a new room\n- Networking events / mixers\n- LinkedIn About sections\n- Conference speaker intros\n- Any moment you're asked to summarize your career in under 90 seconds\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Past** — one line of *relevant* history. Not your full biography. Just enough to establish the foundation for Present.\n2. **Present** — what you're doing *right now* that connects to this moment. The answer to \"why are we talking?\"\n3. **Future** — where you're heading and why *this* conversation matters to that direction.\n\n## Why the Future node is load-bearing\n\nMost people stop at Present. They say where they came from and where they are now and leave the listener wondering \"…and?\" The Future node is what makes the introduction feel purposeful rather than retrospective. It also does the meta-work of *why are we in this conversation* without forcing the listener to construct it.\n\nIn an interview context, the Future node should land *exactly* on the role you're interviewing for. That's not coincidence — it's structure.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Strong (interview opener):**\n> \"I started my career as a data engineer at Spotify, building the pipeline that still powers their Wrapped campaigns. [**Past**] For the last two years I've been leading infrastructure at a 40-person ML startup, where I rebuilt our training pipeline from the ground up and cut our weekly GPU spend by 60%. [**Present**] What I'm looking for next is a role where I can take that experience and apply it at a bigger scale — specifically, the kind of work your platform team is doing on multi-tenant GPU scheduling. [**Future**]\"\n\n**Strong (networking mixer):**\n> \"I was a theater major who ended up in product marketing. [**Past**] Right now I run B2B marketing at a communication-training startup called Cognify. [**Present**] I'm here tonight because we're thinking about our first enterprise L&D pilots and I want to meet people who've done that before. [**Future**]\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Past bloat** — 60 seconds of career history that doesn't lead anywhere. The Past node should be one sentence, maybe two.\n- **Irrelevant Past** — details about where you grew up or what you studied when they have no bearing on the present conversation\n- **Missing Future** — trailing off at Present, leaving the listener to connect the dots\n- **Generic Future** — \"I'm looking for the next chapter of my career\" is not a Future. Specific role, specific ambition, specific bridge to *this* conversation.\n- **Chronology trap** — telling the career in strict chronological order instead of in importance order\n- **Tell-me-about-yourself as autobiography** — treating the question as an invitation to narrate your life\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"So I was born in…\"\n- \"I went to college at…\"\n- \"And then I worked at X, then Y, then Z…\" (pure chronology)\n- \"I've done a lot of different things…\"\n- \"I don't really know where to start…\"\n\n## PPF vs STAR\n\nPPF is for **introductions** and career framing — the first 60 seconds of a conversation.\n\nSTAR (`star.md`) is for **behavioral questions** — specific stories about specific situations.\n\nA strong interview uses both: PPF opens the conversation, STAR runs every behavioral question that follows.\n\n## Origin\n\nLong-standing narrative pattern in rhetoric and career counseling. The three-act structure (past/present/future) predates formal frameworks but was codified for business communication in the 1990s by career coaches and outplacement firms. Also deeply rooted in Aristotle's dramatic unity — every Western narrative has some version of before/during/after.\n\n## See also\n\n- `star.md` — the behavioral-interview framework PPF pairs with\n- `behavioral-interview.md` — the domain MD\n- `storytelling.md` — the broader narrative-craft domain\n" },
  { id: "ppp", content: "# Framework: Progress → Plans → Problems (PPP)\n\nStandup-style status update. Originated in agile / scrum daily standups and spread across most modern tech organizations as the default weekly-update format. The tightest structure for \"here's where things stand\" without over-sharing or under-sharing.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Daily standups (originally)\n- Weekly status updates to a manager\n- Cross-team syncs where you have 60 seconds to report\n- Async updates in Slack or email\n- Any moment you need to communicate *where work stands* without writing a report\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Progress** — what got done since the last update. Concrete, checkable. Not \"I worked on X\" — \"I shipped X, reviewed Y, unblocked Z.\"\n2. **Plans** — what's happening next. What will be true by the next update. Specific.\n3. **Problems** — what's blocked or at risk, *and what you need to unblock it*. The second half is non-optional: naming a problem without naming the ask is just complaining.\n\n## Why Problems matters more than it looks\n\nMost people under-report Problems. They downplay blockers to look competent or capable, which means blockers get discovered late and fixed expensively. PPP's quiet genius is that it makes Problems a required field — if you skip it, the update is incomplete.\n\nThe second half of the Problems node (*\"and what I need to unblock it\"*) is what separates a mature PPP rep from a junior one. A junior says \"I'm blocked on the API.\" A senior says \"I'm blocked on the API — I need a 15-minute call with Priya's team by EOD Wednesday or this slips to next sprint.\"\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Strong (weekly update to manager):**\n> \"**Progress:** Shipped the new onboarding flow to 10% of users Tuesday; conversion on the critical step is up 14 points vs control. Cleared all the p0 bugs in the scoring pipeline. Reviewed Priya's PR for the validation endpoint. **Plans:** Ramping the onboarding rollout to 50% on Thursday assuming metrics hold. Finishing the scoring-signal test fixtures by Friday. **Problems:** The Deepgram rate limits are tighter than we expected on the free tier and it's going to slow our test runs starting next week. I need a decision on whether to move to paid tier by Wednesday — either answer works, but I can't plan around an undecided one.\"\n\n**Strong (daily standup, compressed):**\n> \"**Yesterday:** finished the signal extractor + unit tests. **Today:** wiring it into the scoring route. **Blocked:** nothing, but watch for the Deepgram rate-limit call tomorrow — I'll need a decision.\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Progress as effort report** — \"I worked on X for 4 hours\" is not progress. \"I shipped X\" or \"I completed X\" is progress.\n- **Vague Plans** — \"continuing to work on the migration\" tells the listener nothing. Specific outcomes.\n- **Hidden Problems** — reporting all green when there are real risks. This is the #1 reason teams are surprised by slips.\n- **Problems without Asks** — naming the blocker without saying what would unblock it\n- **Scope bloat** — listing everything you touched instead of what actually moved\n- **Passive voice Progress** — \"the migration was worked on\" instead of \"I migrated the users table\"\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"I worked on a lot of things…\"\n- \"Things are going well…\" (information-free)\n- \"Mostly just tying up loose ends…\"\n- \"Everything's on track\" (when it isn't)\n- \"No blockers\" (when there are)\n- \"Same as yesterday\"\n\n## PPP vs similar frameworks\n\n- **STAR** (`star.md`) — for behavioral stories (\"tell me about a time…\"), not status updates\n- **CDI** (`cdi.md`) — for explaining a decision, not reporting status\n- **BLUF** (`bluf.md`) — when you have 10 seconds and need the update compressed into one sentence\n- **WSW** (`wsw.md`) — for retrospective reflection, not forward-looking status\n\n## Origin\n\nAgile software development, specifically Scrum's daily standup as formalized by Ken Schwaber and Jeff Sutherland in the late 1990s. The original daily standup prescribes three questions: *\"What did you do yesterday? What will you do today? Are there any impediments?\"* PPP is the lightly renamed variant that spread beyond software into cross-functional weekly updates in the 2000s.\n\nModern variants exist (Yesterday/Today/Blockers, Accomplishments/Next/Risks) but PPP remains the most common shorthand.\n\n## See also\n\n- `bluf.md` — Bottom Line → Context → Next Step, for highly compressed updates\n- `wsw.md` — What → So What → Now What, for retrospective reflection\n- `cdi.md` — Context → Decision → Impact, for decision reports\n" },
  { id: "prep", content: "# Framework: Point → Reason → Example → Point (PREP)\n\nThe impromptu-speaking scaffold from Toastmasters International. The default framework for answering an unexpected question with structure but zero planning time.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Answering a question you weren't expecting (\"what do you think about X?\")\n- Group discussions where you have 10 seconds to organize a response\n- Quick interview follow-ups\n- Any moment you need to sound prepared without being prepared\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Point** — state your point directly. No windup, no \"well, that's a great question…\", no preamble.\n2. **Reason** — one sentence on *why* you believe it.\n3. **Example** — a concrete case that proves it. Specific, recent, real.\n4. **Point (restated)** — repeat your point, tighter than the first time. This is the frame that makes PREP feel complete instead of trailing off.\n\n## Why the restate matters\n\nThe restated Point is what separates PREP from PRE. Without it, the response feels unfinished. The restate is ≤ 50% the length of the original point, and it often reframes slightly — the example has earned you the right to say the point more forcefully the second time.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n> \"**Remote work should default to async, not sync.** [Point] Every sync meeting is a tax on everyone's focus time, and most of what happens in them could be a written update. [Reason] On my last team, we killed half our standing meetings and replaced them with written updates — cycle time on the main product dropped 30% within a quarter. [Example] So yes — async by default, sync by exception. [Point restated]\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Burying the Point** — starting with \"so I think there's kind of like a few things to consider…\". PREP demands the Point comes first.\n- **Abstract Example** — \"you see this in a lot of companies\" is not an example. A company name, a number, a moment — that's an example.\n- **Missing the restate** — trailing off after the example feels unfinished. The restate lands the plane.\n- **Over-reasoning** — a paragraph-long Reason loses the punch. One sentence.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"Well, it's a great question…\"\n- \"There's a few ways to look at it…\"\n- \"I don't know if I have a strong opinion, but…\"\n- Hedging the point (\"I kind of think maybe that…\")\n\n## Origin\n\nToastmasters International impromptu-speaking methodology. Used in Toastmasters \"Table Topics\" sessions since the 1950s to teach extemporaneous structure. Variants (PREEP, 5Ps) exist but the PREP form is the most widely-taught.\n\n## See also\n\n- `bluf.md` — when the situation is more formal and the point needs to land even faster\n- `cei.md` — Claim → Evidence → Implication, when the point is contested and you need to survive pushback\n" },
  { id: "pspa", content: "# Framework: Problem → Solution → Proof → Ask (PSPA)\n\nModern B2B sales framing. Pain → offer → evidence → next step. Derived from Neil Rackham's SPIN Selling and Matthew Dixon's Challenger Sale, condensed into four nodes for live delivery in cold calls, demos, and discovery rooms.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Cold call value statements (compressed, under 30 seconds)\n- Product demos (2–5 minutes, full form)\n- Discovery calls closing into a next step\n- Any internal pitch where you need the listener to commit to a follow-up\n- Investor updates where traction is the ask\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Problem** — the specific pain the buyer is feeling today. Not your product's feature list. The *feeling* on their side of the table.\n2. **Solution** — how your thing addresses it. Specific, not generic. \"We reduce onboarding time from 7 months to 3\" beats \"we make onboarding easier.\"\n3. **Proof** — evidence it works. A case, a number, a demo moment, a quote. Not a logo wall.\n4. **Ask** — the specific next step you want. Not \"let me know if you're interested.\" A calendar time, a trial, a referral.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Compressed — cold call opener:**\n> \"Most enterprise AEs I talk to lose 4–5 months of ramp because they don't practice complex-sale scenarios before they're live in front of customers. [**Problem**] We built a scenario gym where they run ten reps a day on the real conversations they'll have — discovery, objection handling, executive briefings — and get scored on it. [**Solution**] At Datadog, new hires using this flow hit quota in their fourth month instead of the seventh. [**Proof**] Would Tuesday or Thursday work for a 15-minute walkthrough? [**Ask**]\"\n\n**Full form — demo close:**\n> \"The problem we solve is the gap between what courses teach and what actually happens in a live sales call. [**Problem**] Cognify generates a framework for the conversation, records the rep's attempt, scores it against the framework, and shows improvement over time. [**Solution**] One of our pilot customers cut new-AE ramp from seven months to four, and their blind-listener rankings showed a 60% improvement after 20 reps. [**Proof**] I'd like to set up a two-week pilot with your SDR team — no cost, no contract. Can we schedule a kickoff for next Wednesday? [**Ask**]\"\n\n## Why the Ask is non-negotiable\n\nEvery experienced sales trainer (Dixon, Rackham, Dan Pink, Chris Orlob) agrees: without a specific Ask, PSPA is a status update, not a sale. \"Let me know if you're interested\" puts the cognitive burden on the buyer and they will not carry it. The specific Ask (\"Tuesday or Thursday?\") puts the burden on the *speaker* and that's where it belongs.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Problem as feature dressed up** — \"the problem is that you don't have our thing yet\" (Matthew Dixon calls this \"commission breath\")\n- **Generic Solution** — \"we help companies scale\" tells the listener nothing\n- **Logo-wall Proof** — \"we work with Google, Apple, and Microsoft\" is not proof of *your specific claim*. Specific before famous.\n- **Soft Ask** — \"let me know if this sounds interesting\" is not an ask\n- **Skipping Problem** — leading with Solution. The listener has no reason to care yet.\n- **Over-quantifying Proof** — buyers discount any number that feels too round or too perfect\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"I just wanted to quickly share…\"\n- \"We're a cloud-based end-to-end…\"\n- \"Let me know if you'd like to hear more…\"\n- \"We help companies be more efficient…\"\n- \"Feel free to reach out if this resonates…\"\n\n## PSPA in Cognify's scoring\n\nCold call and sales scenario reps using PSPA are scored on **all four nodes landed in order**. Missing the Ask is the most common failure and is flagged as a structural failure, not a delivery failure — it's a thinking error, not a word-choice error.\n\n## Origin\n\nSynthesized from:\n- **Neil Rackham**, *SPIN Selling* (1988) — Situation/Problem/Implication/Need-payoff\n- **Matthew Dixon**, *The Challenger Sale* (2011) — teach-tailor-take control\n- **Daniel Pink**, *To Sell Is Human* (2012) — clarity, attunement, buoyancy\n- **Chris Orlob**, pclub.io training — modern enterprise SaaS framing\n\nThe PSPA condensation is not attributed to a single author; it is the common shape that modern sales trainers converge on when teaching live-delivery framing.\n\n## See also\n\n- `fab.md` — Feature → Advantage → Benefit, for product-centric pitches where the pain is already agreed\n- `aida.md` — Attention → Interest → Desire → Action, for cold audiences who don't yet know they have a problem\n- `cold-calling.md` — the domain MD with full practitioner grounding\n" },
  { id: "scqa", content: "# Framework: Situation → Complication → Question → Answer (SCQA)\n\nConsulting-grade framing for executive audiences. Developed by **Barbara Minto** at McKinsey in the 1960s and published in *The Pyramid Principle: Logic in Writing and Thinking* (1987). The cornerstone of modern management consulting communication.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Strategy recommendations\n- Executive briefings\n- Cross-functional pitches where \"why does this matter\" must land before \"what do we do\"\n- Any moment the listener needs to *feel the tension* before they hear your answer\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Situation** — where things stand today. The facts your audience already accepts. This is common ground, not news.\n2. **Complication** — what changed, what's at risk, what's broken. This is where tension enters.\n3. **Question** — the implicit question the complication has created in the listener's mind. You name it so they don't have to form it themselves.\n4. **Answer** — your recommendation. The top of your pyramid.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n> \"Our enterprise sales team has been closing 40% of qualified leads for three quarters. [**Situation**] But our AE onboarding time has doubled since we shifted to complex-sale territory — new reps take seven months to hit quota instead of three. [**Complication**] So how do we get new hires to full productivity faster without sacrificing rigor? [**Question**] We should build a 30-day scenario-training bootcamp modeled on what product engineers already do with code-review bootcamps. [**Answer**]\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Situation bloat** — 60 seconds of common ground no one needs. Execs already know it. Trim.\n- **Weak complication** — the audience doesn't feel the tension, so the answer feels unearned. If there's no complication, there's no reason for the recommendation.\n- **Missing Question** — jumping from complication to answer without naming the question forces the listener to construct it themselves, and they often construct a different one than you're answering.\n- **Hedged answer** — \"we could potentially explore considering…\". SCQA demands a real answer.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- Starting with the answer (that's Minto Pyramid — use `minto.md` when urgency > tension)\n- Letting the complication drift into a list of problems instead of one sharp tension\n- Treating SCQA as writing-only — it works live, but demands real discipline on Situation length\n\n## Origin\n\nBarbara Minto, *The Pyramid Principle* (1987). Minto was McKinsey's first woman consultant. SCQA inverts how most people naturally communicate — instead of building *to* a conclusion, you lead with the tension that earns it, then deliver the conclusion.\n\n## See also\n\n- `minto.md` — Answer → Reasons → Evidence, the short-form variant\n- `bluf.md` — military-derived Bottom Line Up Front, even tighter than Minto\n- `cei.md` — Claim → Evidence → Implication for contested arguments\n" },
  { id: "star", content: "# Framework: Situation → Task → Action → Result (STAR)\n\nThe behavioral-interview backbone. Used by Amazon, Google, Microsoft, and most mature tech hiring processes for \"tell me about a time when…\" questions.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Any behavioral interview question (\"tell me about a time…\", \"describe a situation where…\", \"walk me through how you…\")\n- Performance-review stories\n- Résumé bullets (compressed form)\n- Promotion packets\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **Situation** — the context you were in. One sentence. Not your full biography.\n2. **Task** — what *you specifically* were responsible for. Not the team, not the company — you.\n3. **Action** — what *you personally* did. Every sentence should start with \"I\", not \"we\".\n4. **Result** — the outcome, with **numbers** whenever possible. Reasonable estimates beat vague wins.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n> \"I was the tech lead on checkout for an ecommerce platform doing $2M/day in revenue. [**Situation**] During Black Friday we saw a 30% spike in abandoned carts and I was asked to figure out why within 48 hours. [**Task**] I pulled the funnel data, identified that a new address validator was timing out for 15% of users, rolled back the validator behind a feature flag, and instrumented the fallback path. [**Action**] Abandoned carts dropped from 30% above baseline back to normal within four hours, recovering approximately $180K in same-day revenue. I also wrote the post-mortem and added a canary deploy gate that caught two similar issues in the next six months. [**Result**]\"\n\n## Common failure modes — all verified in the 2025–2026 Amazon interview literature\n\n- **\"We\" instead of \"I\"** — interviewers explicitly listen for first-person ownership. Switch every \"we decided\" to \"I recommended\" or \"I initiated.\"\n- **Situation bloat** — the #1 STAR mistake. Don't set the scene for 90 seconds. One line.\n- **Vague Action** — \"we worked together and figured it out\" tells the interviewer nothing. Specifics about what *you* did.\n- **Missing Result numbers** — \"approximately 30% reduction\" beats \"significant improvement.\" Estimates are fine; vague adjectives are not.\n- **No learning layer** — especially for Amazon's \"Are Right A Lot\" principle, the story should include what you'd do differently or what you learned. Candidates dodge this because the question feels like it's about the mistake; it's actually about the *recovery and process improvement*.\n\n## Amazon-specific notes\n\n- Each story should map to **at least one** Amazon Leadership Principle (bonus if two).\n- Prepare **2 stories per principle** — 8–10 well-prepared stories will cover almost any behavioral question.\n- Quantified Results are effectively required.\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"So the team was in a situation where we had to…\" (we + situation bloat)\n- \"And then we eventually figured it out and things got better\" (no numbers, no action detail)\n- Leading with the Result (\"I saved $180K by…\") — that's elevator-pitch form; STAR builds to the Result\n\n## Origin\n\nDeveloped in the 1970s as part of structured behavioral interviewing methodology; adopted and popularized by Amazon, Google, and Microsoft in the 2000s. Validated by decades of IO-psych research on behavioral versus situational interviewing.\n\n## Sources\n\n- Amazon Interview Guidelines (Amazon leadership-principles behavioral interview guide, 2025–2026)\n- Gayle Laakmann McDowell, *Cracking the PM Interview*\n- Tryexponent.com and Interview Kickstart 2026 Amazon behavioral guides\n" },
  { id: "wsw", content: "# Framework: What → So What → Now What (WSW)\n\nReflective practice framework. Turns observation into action. Developed by John Driscoll in the 1990s for nursing reflection; adopted into management training, retrospectives, and impromptu speaking.\n\nMatt Abrahams (Stanford, *Think Faster, Talk Smarter*) recommends WSW as the default impromptu-speaking framework for \"what do you think about X?\" questions — it's specifically engineered to load fast into working memory under pressure.\n\n## When to use\n\n- Retrospectives and post-mortems\n- Debriefs after a meeting, pitch, or event\n- Reflective moments in performance reviews\n- **Impromptu \"what do you think?\" questions** — WSW is Abrahams' go-to framework here\n- Journal entries and learning reviews\n- Any moment you need to turn an observation into a commitment\n\n## The nodes\n\n1. **What** — what happened. Objectively. Facts, not feelings. The observable events.\n2. **So What** — what it means. Why it matters. The interpretation layer — this is where you add judgment.\n3. **Now What** — what changes as a result. The concrete next action. The commitment.\n\n## Why Now What is load-bearing\n\nWSW distinguishes itself from most reflection frameworks because the *Now What* node is non-optional. Reflection without action is just rumination. The Now What is what converts the insight into movement — and in impromptu speaking, it's the node that makes the answer feel *complete* rather than just *thoughtful*.\n\nWithout Now What, WSW collapses into \"I saw a thing and here's what I think.\" With it, WSW becomes a closed loop: observation → interpretation → commitment.\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n**Retrospective:**\n> \"Our cycle time on the last sprint went from 6 days average to 11 days. [**What**] The slowdown was concentrated in code review — we had two senior engineers on vacation simultaneously and the remaining reviewers got bottlenecked. [**So What**] Going forward, we're going to enforce that no more than one senior engineer per code-owner group is out at the same time, and we're training two mid-levels to be secondary approvers on the critical paths. [**Now What**]\"\n\n**Impromptu \"what do you think about X?\" — Abrahams' recommended use:**\n> \"The big shift I'm seeing is that AI tools are collapsing the gap between junior and senior output quality. [**What**] That matters because the training pipeline for junior hires is built around a gap that's no longer there — we used to teach juniors by giving them work that AI now does in 10 minutes. [**So What**] So I think the companies that win the next five years are going to be the ones that completely redesign junior onboarding around judgment and context, not around output. [**Now What**]\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Interpreting in the What node** — mixing observation with judgment. What should be purely observable; So What is where interpretation belongs.\n- **Skipping Now What** — ending at So What and leaving the reflection dangling. Without action, there's no framework — just musing.\n- **Generic Now What** — \"we should do better next time\" is not a Now What. A specific, named, checkable action is.\n- **Emotional What** — \"it was really frustrating when…\" is a feeling, not an observation\n- **Over-generalizing from a single instance** — WSW is for reflection, not theorizing; keep the scope tight\n\n## Antipatterns\n\n- \"What I noticed was that people were kind of, like, frustrated…\" (interpretation + hedging in the What node)\n- \"So what we probably should think about doing…\" (diluting the Now What into vapor)\n- \"I think we just need to be better at communicating…\" (unmeasurable Now What)\n- Ending with \"…so yeah, that's kind of where I'm at\"\n\n## WSW vs similar frameworks\n\n- **Driscoll's original 3-questions** (What? / So What? / Now What?) — the source material. Identical structure; WSW is the acronym form.\n- **Gibbs' Reflective Cycle** — 6-node version with more structure. Useful for deep retrospective; too heavy for impromptu.\n- **PREP** (`prep.md`) — when the question is not reflective but opinion-based\n- **STAR** (`star.md`) — when the question is \"tell me about a time\"\n\n## Origin\n\nJohn Driscoll, \"Reflective practice for practise,\" *Senior Nurse*, 1994. Driscoll adapted philosopher Terry Borton's \"What? So What? Now What?\" model (1970) into a clinical reflection framework for nursing practice. The 3-question form spread through healthcare education, management training, and impromptu-speaking methodology over the following two decades.\n\nMatt Abrahams (Stanford GSB) reintroduced WSW to a business-communication audience in his 2023 book *Think Faster, Talk Smarter*, specifically recommending it as the default impromptu-speaking framework for opinion and reflection questions.\n\n## See also\n\n- `prep.md` — Point → Reason → Example → Point, for opinion questions where reflection isn't the frame\n- `impromptu.md` — the domain MD with broader context on Abrahams' six-step methodology\n- `ppp.md` — Progress → Plans → Problems, the retrospective framework for status updates\n" }
];

export const SKILLS_BLOCKS: ReadonlyArray<{ id: string; content: string }> = [
  { id: "clarity", content: "# Skill: Clarity\r\n\r\n> \"Ideas land on the first hearing. No ambiguity. Concrete language.\"\r\n\r\nClarity is the dimension where the listener doesn't have to re-interpret. They don't mentally rewind, they don't ask you to repeat, they don't lean to their neighbor and whisper \"wait, what?\" Clarity is the first job of communication and the most commonly under-trained skill in professional speech.\r\n\r\n## Definition\r\n\r\nIdeas transmitted without friction. A clear speaker is understood the first time by an audience-appropriate listener. This is not about speaking slowly or using small words — it's about every sentence being *resolvable* the moment it's heard.\r\n\r\n## Why we chose this\r\n\r\nClarity is foundational because every other dimension depends on it — a brilliant argument lost on the listener doesn't move anyone. We picked it because the failure mode is concrete and trainable: jargon density, abstract-noun ratio, and pronoun resolution all surface as measurable signals in any 60-second response. Daily reps build the pattern of stating the main point first and grounding abstract claims with concrete examples — the single most asked-for skill in our internal coaching feedback.\r\n\r\n## Experts and sources\r\n\r\n- **Steven Pinker**, *The Sense of Style* (2014) — \"classic style\" prose, concrete over abstract, the curse of knowledge\r\n- **George Orwell**, \"Politics and the English Language\" (1946) — six rules for clear writing; arguably the clearest thinking-about-clarity ever published\r\n- **Strunk & White**, *The Elements of Style* (1918/1959) — \"Omit needless words\"\r\n- **William Zinsser**, *On Writing Well* (1976) — clarity as discipline, not gift\r\n- **Barbara Minto**, *The Pyramid Principle* (1987) — MECE reasoning, exec register\r\n- **Steve Krug**, *Don't Make Me Think* (2000) — cognitive-load principles that translate directly from UX to speech\r\n- **Nancy Duarte** — the audience-first principle (\"persuasion doesn't start with you\")\r\n- **Matt Abrahams** (Stanford) — audience-register matching from *Think Faster, Talk Smarter*\r\n\r\n## What great clarity sounds like\r\n\r\n- Main point stated within the first 10 seconds\r\n- Concrete nouns (\"the validation endpoint\", \"the Tuesday deploy\", \"the checkout flow\") instead of abstract ones (\"the system\", \"the process\", \"stuff\")\r\n- Unambiguous pronouns — every \"it\", \"they\", \"that\" has a visible antecedent\r\n- Audience-appropriate vocabulary — more on this in `tone.md`, but audience mismatch is the single most common clarity failure mode\r\n- No throat-clearing preambles (\"so basically what I want to say is…\")\r\n\r\n## What low clarity sounds like\r\n\r\n- Unresolved pronouns — \"and *it* kind of became a problem because *they* wanted *that* to work differently\"\r\n- Abstract nouns where concrete would work — \"there's a situation with the thing we're trying to solve\"\r\n- Jargon density mismatched to audience — engineering jargon to a CFO, marketing jargon to an engineer\r\n- Listener-pauses-to-re-interpret moments\r\n\r\n## Signals (deterministic contribution)\r\n\r\n- **Filler-word rate** degrades clarity (also hits conciseness)\r\n- **Pronoun-reference density** — high pronoun counts without proportional noun anchors is a risk signal\r\n- **Hedge rate** — \"kind of\", \"sort of\", \"maybe\" blur claims\r\n- **Sentence-length variance** — extreme long or short both hurt\r\n\r\nThe LLM layer (Claude Sonnet in the hybrid scoring architecture) scores semantic clarity on top of these signals.\r\n\r\n## Scoring boundaries\r\n\r\n| Score | What it looks like |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| **95** | Every sentence lands on first hearing. Main point in opening 10s. Concrete, audience-appropriate, zero re-interpretation needed. |\r\n| **80** | Clear with one or two moments where the listener has to work slightly harder than they should. |\r\n| **60** | Main point lands, but takes longer than it should. Some ambiguity, but recoverable. |\r\n| **40** | Listener is working to follow. Multiple re-interpretation moments. Main point becomes clear only at the end, or not at all. |\r\n| **20** | Listener is lost. Main point never resolves. |\r\n\r\n## Exemplar callouts\r\n\r\n- *(positive)* \"Strong concrete opener — 'the checkout flow timed out for 15% of users' is exactly the specificity this moment needed.\"\r\n- *(warn)* \"The pronoun 'it' at 0:34 has no clear antecedent — listener has to guess whether you mean the migration or the validation.\"\r\n- *(critical)* \"By 1:15, the main point still hasn't landed. We've heard context, tangent, and qualifier, but not the decision you're asking for.\"\r\n\r\n## Common failure modes\r\n\r\n- **Abstract noun dependency** — \"the system\", \"the process\", \"the situation\", \"the thing\"\r\n- **Pronoun soup** — too many it/they/that without antecedents\r\n- **Audience mismatch** — register wrong for the listener\r\n- **Preamble** — \"So basically, what I want to say is…\"\r\n- **Curse of knowledge** — forgetting the listener doesn't have your context\r\n\r\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\r\n\r\n- \"Basically…\"\r\n- \"The thing is…\"\r\n- \"What I mean by that is…\"\r\n- \"Let me explain what I mean…\"\r\n- \"You know what I mean?\"\r\n- \"So yeah…\" as opener\r\n\r\n## Frameworks that train clarity\r\n\r\nEvery framework trains some clarity, but the hardest-hitting are:\r\n- **BLUF** (`bluf.md`) — forces the point into sentence one\r\n- **Minto Pyramid** (`minto.md`) — Answer-first, no preamble\r\n- **PREP** (`prep.md`) — Point-first, Point-restated\r\n- **CEI** (`cei.md`) — Claim-first, no hedging\r\n" },
  { id: "conciseness", content: "# Skill: Conciseness\r\n\r\n> \"Maximum signal per word. Tight sentences over bloated ones.\"\r\n\r\nConciseness is the discipline of saying the most with the fewest words that will still land. It's distinct from clarity (which is about being understood on the first hearing) — a sentence can be perfectly clear AND bloated. Conciseness asks: did every word earn its place?\r\n\r\n## Definition\r\n\r\nSignal-per-word density, plus time-budget discipline. A concise speaker cuts filler, avoids repetition, skips preambles, and knows when to stop. Conciseness shows up in two places: the word level (no throat-clearing, no hedges) and the structural level (one main point, not three; one supporting example, not five).\r\n\r\n## Why we chose this\r\n\r\nConciseness is where credibility either holds or leaks. We chose it because filler density and hedge rate are the two highest-signal failure modes a listener registers — and they're directly measurable from a transcript with no model needed. Trainable because the rep itself is the training: 60 seconds of no-um, no-hedge speaking is a cognitive exercise that rewires the reflex. The fundamental reason: every word that doesn't move the argument actively undoes the argument.\r\n\r\n## Experts and sources\r\n\r\n- **Strunk & White**, *The Elements of Style* — \"Omit needless words\" is the textbook conciseness rule; conciseness is arguably the most durable thing the book teaches.\r\n- **William Zinsser**, *On Writing Well* — \"Every word that serves no function... is an enemy of the sentence.\"\r\n- **Paul Graham** — essay prose as a model of conciseness: one idea per sentence, one argument per paragraph.\r\n- **Barbara Minto**, *The Pyramid Principle* — BLUF (Bottom Line Up Front) is conciseness at the structural level.\r\n- **Patrick Winston** (MIT), \"How to Speak\" — the \"promise, inspiration, enumeration\" opening is about getting to signal fast.\r\n- **30 Minutes to President's Club** (2024) — modern cold-call research showing concise pitches convert dramatically better.\r\n\r\n## What great conciseness sounds like\r\n\r\n- Main point stated first, no preamble (BLUF pattern)\r\n- Each sentence advances the argument — no sentence is load-bearing only for tone\r\n- Filler rate < 2 per minute (um, uh, like, you know, basically)\r\n- Finishes within 10% of time budget — neither rushes the last point nor strands time at the end\r\n- Tight word economy — typically < 25 words per distinct point\r\n- No repetition — the same idea isn't restated in different words because the first statement was weak\r\n\r\n## What low conciseness sounds like\r\n\r\n- High filler rate (> 4 per minute)\r\n- Long preambles — \"so what I want to say is, basically, the thing I think is important here is…\"\r\n- Repeating the same point in slightly different words because the first statement didn't feel strong\r\n- Going over time budget — the speaker keeps talking past where the content runs out\r\n- Hedge-stacking — \"I think it's probably the case that maybe we could consider perhaps…\"\r\n\r\n## Signals (deterministic contribution)\r\n\r\n- **Filler rate** — strong signal; conciseness and delivery both reference this metric\r\n- **Time-budget ratio** — going over budget is a conciseness failure even when the content is fine\r\n- **Words-per-point** (derived from transcript segmentation) — high values = bloat\r\n- **Repetition detection** — same clause/idea stated twice in one rep\r\n\r\n## Signals (LLM contribution)\r\n\r\n- Content-density judgment — did each sentence add signal, or was it padding?\r\n- Preamble detection — did the rep lead with the main point or warm into it?\r\n- Hedge-stacking pattern — is every assertion weakened by qualifiers?\r\n\r\n## How to improve conciseness\r\n\r\n- **BLUF your openings.** State the answer before the rationale.\r\n- **Cut one sentence per rewrite.** On every practice rep, challenge yourself to drop a sentence and see if the rep still lands.\r\n- **Time constraints force the skill.** Cognify's `be_concise` rep type drills this directly with 20-second time boxes.\r\n- **Silence after the point.** Conciseness includes knowing when to stop. Ending clean is a skill.\r\n- **Listen for your own hedges.** Record a normal conversation; count every \"I think\", \"maybe\", \"kind of\". The number surprises most speakers.\r\n\r\n## Common conciseness traps\r\n\r\n- **Filler as a stalling tactic** — filler isn't accidental; it's a cognitive-load release. Training thinking quality (coherent generation) reduces filler indirectly.\r\n- **Verbosity as safety** — speakers pad to feel thorough. Thoroughness and conciseness aren't opposites; a concise point feels MORE authoritative, not less.\r\n- **Restating as emphasis** — repeating a claim to underline it often dilutes instead. Better: one clean statement + a concrete example.\r\n- **Filling time** — if you have 60 seconds and your answer is 40, stop at 40. Talking to fill time is the cheapest conciseness failure.\r\n" },
  { id: "delivery", content: "# Skill: Delivery\r\n\r\n> \"How it sounds. Pacing, pauses, vocal energy, finishing clean.\"\r\n\r\nDelivery (renamed from \"Pacing\" in the v2.0.0 rubric and expanded to absorb the vocal side of old \"tone\") measures whether the rep *sounds* right — steady pacing, purposeful pauses, vocal variation matched to content stakes, and clean finishing within time. This is the most deterministically-scorable dimension in the rubric. Delivery maps closely to Deepgram's word-level timestamps — WPM, filler rate, quartile variance, time-budget compliance — and is the cleanest path to **model-stable trend lines** (the measurability story David demanded in the April 2026 advisory meeting).\r\n\r\n## Definition\r\n\r\nWPM is stable across the rep. Purposeful pauses for emphasis. Vocal variation matches content stakes. The rep finishes within the time budget without rushing the closer or leaving the ending half-baked. Pauses are intentional (breath, emphasis) rather than panicked (working memory overflow — that's a Thinking Quality tell, not a Delivery one).\r\n\r\n## Why we chose this\r\n\r\nDelivery is the deterministic layer of the rubric — same audio, same score, every time. We chose it because pacing, pause placement, and filler rate are all measurable from word timings without an LLM in the loop, which means trend lines are real (not model drift). Trainable through targeted drills like Metronome Rep and Pause Punctuation. Fundamental because rate alone outside the 150-160 wpm band makes everything else harder to follow — a brilliant idea at 220 wpm reaches the listener as a blur.\r\n\r\n## Experts and sources\r\n\r\n- **Elizabeth Shriberg** (SRI / Microsoft Research) — foundational work on speech disfluencies and filler-word taxonomy. Her 1994 Switchboard corpus analysis is still the reference for baseline disfluency rates in L1 English speech.\r\n- **Strunk & White**, *The Elements of Style* — Rule 17: *\"Omit needless words. Vigorous writing is concise.\"* The most-quoted rule in English style, and it applies to speech as much as to writing.\r\n- **George Orwell**, \"Politics and the English Language\" (1946) — *\"If it is possible to cut a word out, always cut it out.\"*\r\n- **William Zinsser**, *On Writing Well* (1976) — Chapter 2, \"Simplicity\" — clutter as the enemy.\r\n- **US Military BLUF doctrine** — Bottom Line Up Front, engineered for situations where pacing discipline matters more than anywhere else (see `bluf.md`).\r\n- **Matt Abrahams** (Stanford GSB), *Think Faster, Talk Smarter* (2023) — tempo management under impromptu pressure; breath work as a pacing tool.\r\n- **Carmine Gallo**, *Talk Like TED* (2014) — the 18-minute cognitive limit and tempo analysis of 500+ TED talks.\r\n\r\n## What great pacing sounds like\r\n\r\n- Filler rate under 2 per minute\r\n- Consistent WPM across the rep — final quartile within ±10% of opening quartile\r\n- Finishes within 90–110% of the time budget\r\n- No visible rush in the final sentence\r\n- Hedges are rare (\"maybe\", \"I think\", \"sort of\" — under one per minute)\r\n- Breaks are purposeful — breath, emphasis, giving the listener a beat\r\n- The last sentence lands cleanly — doesn't trail off, doesn't get cut off by time\r\n\r\n## What low pacing sounds like\r\n\r\n- Filler words: \"um\", \"uh\", \"like\", \"you know\", \"basically\", \"actually\", \"literally\"\r\n- Hedges: \"kind of\", \"sort of\", \"I think\", \"maybe\", \"I guess\", \"just\"\r\n- Rushing in the final quartile when the clock hits 75% — WPM accelerates sharply\r\n- Voice tightening, pitch rising near time-out\r\n- Going significantly over or under the time budget\r\n- Run-on sentences that could have been three sentences\r\n- Rambling — over-qualifying every claim\r\n\r\n## Signals (strongly deterministic — this is pacing's superpower)\r\n\r\nPacing is the **most deterministic dimension** in Cognify. All of its signals come from Deepgram word-level timestamps:\r\n\r\n- **Filler rate** = filler_word_count / (duration_ms / 60000)\r\n- **Hedge rate** = hedge_word_count / (duration_ms / 60000)\r\n- **WPM** (words per minute) = word_count / (duration_ms / 60000)\r\n- **Quartile WPM variance** — split the rep into 4 time quartiles, compute WPM per quartile, measure the variance. High variance = unstable pacing.\r\n- **Final-quartile WPM delta** — how much does WPM change in the last quartile vs the median? >30% acceleration is a rush signal.\r\n- **Time-budget compliance** = duration_ms / time_budget_ms. Flag < 0.60 (under-spoken) or > 1.10 (over-time).\r\n- **Long-pause count** — pauses > 1500ms outside natural breath windows.\r\n\r\nIn the hybrid scoring architecture (Phase 6), pacing will be scored by a **pure deterministic function** of these signals with zero LLM layer. That means its trend lines are mathematically stable across time — the same audio scored today and next month returns the exact same number. **This is the model-stability guarantee that answers David's measurability critique.**\r\n\r\n## Filler-word lexicon (English, v1)\r\n\r\nNon-lexical: `um`, `uh`, `er`, `ah`, `hmm`\r\nLexical: `like` (context-sensitive), `you know`, `I mean`, `so`, `basically`, `actually`, `literally`, `honestly`, `right?`\r\n\r\n## Hedge lexicon (English, v1)\r\n\r\n`I think`, `I guess`, `maybe`, `perhaps`, `probably`, `possibly`, `sort of`, `kind of`, `a bit`, `a little`, `just`, `pretty much`, `more or less`\r\n\r\nBoth lexicons are versioned and will evolve with calibration data from external-validation rankings.\r\n\r\n## Scoring boundaries\r\n\r\n| Score | What it looks like |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| **95** | Filler < 2/min. Hedges < 1/min. WPM variance < 10%. Finishes within 95–105% of budget. Final sentence lands. |\r\n| **80** | Filler 2–4/min. Hedges 1–2/min. Minor pacing drift. Within 90–110% of budget. |\r\n| **60** | Filler 4–8/min. Some hedging. Noticeable final-quartile rush. Time budget at the edge. |\r\n| **40** | Filler 8–15/min. Multiple hedges. Clear rush. Over or significantly under budget. |\r\n| **20** | Filler > 15/min. Constant hedging. Unstable pacing. Cut-off ending or abandoned. |\r\n\r\n## Exemplar callouts\r\n\r\n- *(positive)* \"Filler rate 1.4/min — that's tight. Every sentence carried its own weight.\"\r\n- *(positive)* \"Final quartile held steady. You landed the closing at the same pace you opened it. That's the skill.\"\r\n- *(warn)* \"Three 'I think' hedges in the opening 20s weakened a decision you had the right to state plainly.\"\r\n- *(warn)* \"WPM jumped 28% in the final quartile. The timer got in your head. Practice pacing through the countdown, not against it.\"\r\n- *(critical)* \"Filler rate of 11/min is the dominant signal this rep. Cut fillers to cut everything else — confidence, clarity, and relevance all move with it.\"\r\n\r\n## Common failure modes\r\n\r\n- **Um/uh filling thinking time** — treat pauses as free; they land better than filler\r\n- **Hedging a claim you actually believe** — \"I think maybe we should…\" when you mean \"we should…\"\r\n- **Racing the clock** — speeding up when the timer runs down, instead of deliberately compressing\r\n- **Over-qualification** — \"to be honest\", \"to be fair\", \"literally\", \"actually\"\r\n- **Cut-off ending** — last sentence incomplete because time ran out\r\n\r\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\r\n\r\n- \"Um…\" as opener\r\n- \"Literally\"\r\n- \"Basically\"\r\n- \"Actually\" used three or more times\r\n- \"I think\" + \"maybe\" in the same sentence\r\n- Any sentence starting with \"So…\"\r\n- Trailing off with \"…and yeah\" when the clock hits zero\r\n\r\n## Frameworks that train pacing\r\n\r\n- **BLUF** (`bluf.md`) — engineered for ruthless compression; the single best pacing drill\r\n- **PREP** (`prep.md`) — forces point-first delivery with a restate at the end — no room to drift or drag\r\n- **Minto Pyramid** (`minto.md`) — Answer-first, three-reason ceiling\r\n\r\n## See also\r\n\r\n- `confidence.md` — overlapping delivery dimension; low hedges = high confidence AND high pacing\r\n- `thinking-on-the-spot` is now folded into `confidence.md` — pauses and restarts get measured there as cognitive-load signals rather than pacing signals\r\n- `impromptu.md` — the domain MD for when pacing stress is highest\r\n" },
  { id: "relevance", content: "# Skill: Relevance\n\n> \"Did the rep actually address the prompt?\"\n\nRelevance is the dimension that catches drift. The speaker was asked one question; they need to answer *that* question, not a related one, not a tangent, not whatever came to mind. It sounds obvious until you grade fifty reps and realize how often speakers end on a different topic than they started.\n\n## Definition\n\nThe rep's content directly engages with the prompt from the opening through the close. Every point serves the main question. Tangents earn their place or don't exist. The close restates, reinforces, or answers the prompt.\n\nRelevance is **net-new** in the v2-beta.1 rubric — previous versions assumed prompt-addressing implicitly, which meant off-topic reps still got decent clarity and structure scores. Relevance is the explicit check that the rep is *about* the thing it was supposed to be about.\n\n## Experts and sources\n\n- **Matt Abrahams** (Stanford GSB), *Think Faster, Talk Smarter* (2023) — \"Listen. Most spontaneous-speaking failures are misreadings of what was actually asked.\" The explicit source for treating relevance as a separate discipline from clarity.\n- **Barbara Minto**, *The Pyramid Principle* (1987) — \"Answer-first\" framing is implicitly a relevance discipline: state the answer first, then you can't drift, because the answer has already been delivered.\n- **Amazon behavioral interview methodology** — interviewers explicitly listen for whether the STAR story *answers the question*. A good story about leadership doesn't count if the question was about conflict. Amazon's internal guidance is relentless on this.\n- **Gayle Laakmann McDowell**, *Cracking the PM Interview* — specifically flags \"answering a related but different question\" as a top-five interview failure mode.\n- **The Heath Brothers**, *Made to Stick* — the \"Core\" in SUCCES: strip the message to its essence and make sure what you're saying is what matters. If you're making three points and only one answers the question, you have two waste points.\n- **Aristotle**, *Rhetoric* — the classical concept of *kairos* (the opportune moment) is adjacent: say the right thing at the right time, which means saying *this* thing because *this* is what was asked.\n\n## What great relevance sounds like\n\n- Direct engagement with the prompt in the first 10 seconds\n- Every sentence can be traced back to the prompt (\"this matters because you asked about…\")\n- The close restates or reinforces the answer to the original question\n- Tangents are either absent or earn their place by reinforcing the main point\n- If the prompt has two parts, both get addressed proportionally\n\n## What low relevance sounds like\n\n- The rep starts on-topic and drifts to a related-but-different topic by the midpoint\n- The closing is about something the speaker found interesting, not what was asked\n- A strong opening followed by a long tangent the speaker never recovers from\n- Answering a simpler version of the question rather than the actual one\n- Going meta — talking about *how* you'd answer instead of *answering*\n\n## Signals (hybrid, LLM-heavy)\n\nRelevance is the most LLM-dependent dimension in the rubric because it requires semantic judgment: what was the prompt asking, and did the transcript address it?\n\nDeterministic contributions:\n- **Prompt-transcript token overlap** — does the transcript contain any of the prompt's content words? (Weak signal but useful for the empty-transcript case.)\n- **Topic-coherence heuristic** — do the first quarter and last quarter of the transcript mention similar topics? (Proxy for \"no drift.\")\n- **Tangent detection** — does the transcript contain phrases like \"anyway\", \"where was I\", \"what was the question\" — explicit drift markers.\n\nLLM layer:\n- Given the prompt and the transcript, does the rep answer the prompt?\n- Is the close on-topic or drifted?\n- Are there tangents that never return to the main question?\n\n## Scoring boundaries\n\n| Score | What it looks like |\n|---|---|\n| **95** | Directly addresses the prompt from opening through close. Every point earns its place. Closing restates or reinforces the answer. |\n| **80** | Answers the prompt well. One small tangent but quickly returns. |\n| **60** | Answers the prompt, but drifts at the end or wastes 20–30% of the rep on unrelated material. |\n| **40** | Starts on-topic but ends on a different topic. The question is only half-answered. |\n| **20** | Answers a different question than the one asked, or never gets to the answer at all. |\n\n## Exemplar callouts\n\n- *(positive)* \"Every point in this rep ties back to the prompt. The close restates the main answer. That's relevance discipline.\"\n- *(warn)* \"You drifted from the pricing question at 0:45 into a tangent about onboarding. The drift was interesting but cost you half the rep.\"\n- *(critical)* \"The prompt asked how you'd handle a skeptical executive. The rep answered how you'd handle a technical audience. These aren't the same — the register and the argument are both different.\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Topic drift** — starting on-topic, ending on something else\n- **Question-swap** — answering a related-but-different question (easier or more interesting to the speaker)\n- **Going meta** — talking *about* the answer instead of giving it\n- **Prompt-miss** — misreading what was actually asked (re-reading the prompt out loud first is a cheap fix)\n- **The two-part miss** — when a prompt has two parts and the speaker only addresses one\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"Well, that's an interesting question, but actually I think the more important thing is…\"\n- \"Related to that…\" followed by a tangent\n- \"Let me take a step back…\" (usually means drift is coming)\n- Ending with \"…anyway, that's what I wanted to say\" when it's not what was asked\n- \"Off the top of my head…\" (permission to be loose)\n\n## Frameworks that train relevance\n\n- **Minto Pyramid** (`minto.md`) — Answer-first framing makes relevance almost impossible to fail: if sentence one is the answer, you can't drift\n- **BLUF** (`bluf.md`) — same logic, tighter\n- **STAR** (`star.md`) — the Result node is specifically the prompt's answer; well-trained STAR users restate the Task in the Result to prove relevance\n- **PREP** (`prep.md`) — the restated Point at the end is a relevance check: *\"Here's what I said, which is what you asked about\"*\n\n## See also\n\n- `clarity.md` — overlapping skill; relevance is about *which* point you made, clarity is about *how* it lands\n- `structure.md` — a well-structured rep is usually relevant; drift is often a structure failure in disguise\n- `behavioral-interview.md` — the domain where relevance is stressed hardest\n" },
  { id: "structure", content: "# Skill: Structure\r\n\r\n> \"Visible scaffolding — opening, flow, close.\"\r\n\r\nStructure is the skill of making your argument *findable*. A well-structured rep has shape the listener can follow without working for it: you know where you are, where you've been, and where you're going. Most rambling isn't a content problem — it's a structure problem.\r\n\r\n## Definition\r\n\r\nThe listener can reconstruct the argument without effort. Structure is present when there's a clear opening that establishes direction, logical connectors between points, and a close that lands the main point. It is absent when the speaker jumps between topics without visible scaffolding.\r\n\r\n## Why we chose this\r\n\r\nStructure makes ideas portable — the listener can repeat your point to someone else. We chose it because it's the single biggest predictor of whether a meeting recap or a pitch will land twice. The signals are observable: transition-marker rate, opening-position score, and arc-completion. Trainable through repeated drills like BLUF and Three-Act Close, where the constraint forces the structural muscle that holistic feedback can't develop fast enough. Fundamental because organization is the difference between content that travels and content that evaporates.\r\n\r\n## Experts and sources\r\n\r\n- **Barbara Minto**, *The Pyramid Principle* (1987) — the definitive work on structured business communication; MECE, pyramid principle, SCQA\r\n- **Chip Heath & Dan Heath**, *Made to Stick* (2007) — SUCCES principles, especially *Simple* and *Concrete*\r\n- **Jerry Weissman**, *Presenting to Win* (2003/2011) — \"verbal links\" as explicit signposting; 75 techniques\r\n- **Nancy Duarte**, *Resonate* (2010) — the contrast sparkline, \"what is\" vs \"what could be\"\r\n- **Chris Anderson**, *TED Talks* (2016) — the through-line principle (every talk has exactly one idea)\r\n- **Carmine Gallo**, *Talk Like TED* (2014) — the rule of three, three-act structure\r\n- **Dale Carnegie** — the oldest guidance on speech structure still in wide circulation\r\n- **Aristotle**, *Rhetoric* — ethos/pathos/logos, the original three-part structure\r\n\r\n## What great structure sounds like\r\n\r\n- An opening that establishes direction in the first 10 seconds (\"Three things about the migration. First…\")\r\n- Logical connectors between points — \"because\", \"therefore\", \"which brings us to\", \"the second reason\"\r\n- Consistent ordering (chronological, causal, or importance — pick one and stick to it)\r\n- A closing that reinforces the main point (the \"point-restated\" in PREP, the close in CDI)\r\n- Visible scaffolding the listener can feel without being told about it\r\n\r\n## What low structure sounds like\r\n\r\n- No visible opening or closing — the rep just starts and stops\r\n- Topic jumps without connective tissue — one idea ends, another begins, no bridge\r\n- Random ordering — ideas in whatever sequence they occurred to the speaker\r\n- Missing transitions — \"so… uh… also…\"\r\n- Opening that doesn't establish direction (\"so there's been a few things going on…\")\r\n\r\n## Signals\r\n\r\nStructure is primarily LLM-scored — it requires semantic understanding of the argument's shape. Deterministic contributions:\r\n- **Connector-word density** — presence of \"first/second/third\", \"because\", \"therefore\", \"which brings us to\"\r\n- **Opening-quality heuristic** — does the first 10 seconds contain a direction-establishing clause?\r\n- **Closing-quality heuristic** — does the last 10 seconds restate or reinforce the opening?\r\n- **Framework-adherence score** (scenario mode only) — did the rep hit each framework node in order?\r\n\r\n## Scoring boundaries\r\n\r\n| Score | What it looks like |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| **95** | Clear opening, logical flow with visible connectors, confident close. Listener could transcribe the outline. |\r\n| **80** | Structure present but could be sharper — one weak transition or a less-than-crisp close. |\r\n| **60** | Structure is there but fragile. The listener works harder than they should to follow the argument. |\r\n| **40** | Ideas arrive in no obvious order. No visible opening or close. |\r\n| **20** | Stream of consciousness. No scaffolding at all. |\r\n\r\n## Exemplar callouts\r\n\r\n- *(positive)* \"Strong opening — 'three things about the migration' gave the listener a hook and a count in the first four seconds.\"\r\n- *(warn)* \"The transition at 0:45 from context to decision was unsigned — listener had to work to notice you'd moved on.\"\r\n- *(critical)* \"The rep ends on a tangent about scaling. The main point from the opening never gets restated, which means 30% of listeners will walk away with the wrong summary.\"\r\n- *(positive, scenario mode)* \"All three CDI nodes landed in order — Context in the first 15s, Decision at 0:30, Impact in the closing.\"\r\n\r\n## Common failure modes\r\n\r\n- **No opening** — starting mid-thought (\"so with the migration…\")\r\n- **No closing** — trailing off instead of landing (\"so… yeah, that's what's going on\")\r\n- **Topic jumping without bridges** — switching ideas with no transition word\r\n- **Chronological structure when importance structure would land better** — telling the story in the order it happened instead of the order that matters\r\n- **Missing the through-line** — trying to make three points at once instead of one\r\n\r\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\r\n\r\n- \"Anyways…\"\r\n- \"And then…\" as the only connector\r\n- \"So…\" as opener\r\n- \"So… yeah\" as closer\r\n- \"One more thing…\" added at the end\r\n- Listing without ordering (\"a few thoughts: X, Y, Z…\" without structure)\r\n\r\n## Frameworks that train structure\r\n\r\nStructure is the skill trained *hardest* by Cognify's framework library. Every framework in the library is a structure scaffold. The most load-bearing for structure:\r\n\r\n- **SCQA** (`scqa.md`) — the most rigorous structural framework\r\n- **Minto Pyramid** (`minto.md`) — Answer → Reasons → Evidence\r\n- **CDI** (`cdi.md`) — Context → Decision → Impact\r\n- **ADR** (`adr.md`) — the full 4-node decision framework\r\n- **PREP** (`prep.md`) — the Toastmasters scaffold, specifically for impromptu\r\n- **BLUF** (`bluf.md`) — ruthless compression of structure into 3 nodes\r\n" },
  { id: "thinking_quality", content: "# Skill: Thinking Quality\r\n\r\n> \"Coherent generation under real-time conditions. Sharp recall, steady thinking.\"\r\n\r\nThinking Quality (renamed from \"Confidence\" in the v2.0.0 rubric) is the measurable side of composure: does the speaker generate coherent content under real-time conditions? It covers recall speed, logical-chain integrity, and clean recovery from stumbles. This is distinct from Delivery (how it sounds vocally) — Thinking Quality is what's happening in the thinking itself.\r\n\r\n## Definition\r\n\r\nCoherent generation under real-time conditions. Low backtrack rate, low mid-sentence restart rate, clean recovery from stumbles, logical connectors used correctly, recall feels sharp. The listener's takeaway: *this person's thinking is holding together under load*.\r\n\r\nImportant: Thinking Quality measures the *content* of thinking — NOT the vocal composure (which is Delivery). A speaker can have solid Delivery (steady pace, purposeful pauses) while their Thinking Quality collapses (they hedge, restart, and abandon points). The signals separate cleanly.\r\n\r\n## Why we chose this\r\n\r\nThinking Quality is the dimension that separates \"sounds good\" from \"is good.\" We chose it because the rest of the rubric measures HOW you said it — TQ measures WHAT you said. Trainable through forced-support drills (every claim ships with a number or example) and depth drills (second-order why). Measurable through claim-support rate and depth-of-analysis markers. Fundamental because polishing delivery on shallow content is a well-documented anti-pattern — TQ keeps the substance honest.\r\n\r\n## Experts and sources\r\n\r\n- **Matt Abrahams** (Stanford GSB), *Think Faster, Talk Smarter* (2023) — the modern definitive work. Six-step methodology for managing speaking anxiety, with explicit focus on the *perception* of confidence vs the internal experience.\r\n- **Amy Cuddy**, *Presence* (2015) — power posing, body-mind coupling, presence as a composite. *(Caveat: some of Cuddy's original power-pose replication results have been contested, but the broader confidence-under-pressure research she synthesizes is well-supported.)*\r\n- **Sian Beilock**, *Choke* (2010) — research on how expertise degrades under pressure, specifically for high-stakes performance. The #1 counterintuitive finding: overthinking your own process is what chokes you.\r\n- **Olivia Fox Cabane**, *The Charisma Myth* (2012) — presence = warmth + power; both are trainable delivery behaviors.\r\n- **Daniel Kahneman**, *Thinking, Fast and Slow* (2011) — System 1 under arousal; why pressure degrades structured thinking, and how to run System 2 smoothly during impromptu.\r\n- **Yerkes-Dodson Law** (1908) — classic psych finding: performance improves with arousal up to a point, then sharply degrades. Cognify's daily reps are designed to train the *climb*, not avoid it.\r\n- **Scott Berkun**, *Confessions of a Public Speaker* (2009) — honest, practical treatment of speaking anxiety from a working professional.\r\n- **Elizabeth Shriberg** (SRI / Microsoft Research) — disfluency research showing restart and backtrack rates increase sharply under cognitive load. Confidence is partially an inverse function of backtrack rate.\r\n- **Alan Baddeley** — working memory model. Understanding why impromptu is cognitively expensive helps explain why confidence is the hardest delivery dimension to train.\r\n\r\n## What great confidence sounds like\r\n\r\n- Direct assertions without hedging (\"the migration will slip two weeks\" — not \"I think maybe it might slip\")\r\n- Steady generation without stalling\r\n- Quick clean recovery from stumbles — a stumble is not a failure, but getting stuck on it is\r\n- Purposeful pauses (breath, emphasis) rather than panicked silence\r\n- No over-apologizing (\"sorry\", \"I'm not sure\", \"this probably isn't right but…\")\r\n- Stable tone across the rep — voice doesn't tighten, pitch doesn't rise near time-out\r\n- Closing that reinforces the main point rather than scrambling to finish\r\n\r\n## What low confidence sounds like\r\n\r\n- Hedges: \"I think\", \"maybe\", \"kind of\", \"sort of\", \"I guess\"\r\n- Verbal backtracking: \"wait, let me start over\", \"actually, scratch that\"\r\n- Long pauses (>2 seconds) outside natural breaks\r\n- Mid-sentence restarts: \"so the thing — sorry — what I was trying to say is…\"\r\n- Over-apologizing: \"sorry, I'm not sure if this is right, but…\"\r\n- Voice tightening, pitch rising as the timer runs down\r\n- Cut-off ending — last sentence incomplete because time ran out\r\n- Chasing a stumble — fixating on a mistake and losing the thread\r\n\r\n## Signals (hybrid — deterministic signals feed an LLM layer)\r\n\r\nConfidence has the richest deterministic signal set of any content-group dimension. From Deepgram word-level timestamps:\r\n\r\n- **Hedge rate** — count of hedge-lexicon matches per minute (inverse of confidence)\r\n- **Restart detection** — phrase-repetition within 3-word windows, plus \"wait/sorry/actually/let me\" lexicon matches\r\n- **Backtrack patterns** — n-gram repetition indicating the speaker started a sentence, abandoned it, and restarted\r\n- **Long-pause count** — pauses > 1500ms outside breath windows\r\n- **Quartile WPM variance** — unstable pacing across the rep signals loss of composure\r\n- **Apology-token detection** — \"sorry\", \"apologize\", \"excuse me\" lexicon\r\n- **Final-quartile WPM delta** — rushing in the last 25% signals panic\r\n\r\nThe LLM layer scores the *holistic perception* — does the rep *sound* confident? — because some speakers can hit all the deterministic signals and still sound unsure (monotone, or oddly formal, or flat). The deterministic signals ground the LLM so the score is stable and explainable.\r\n\r\n## Scoring boundaries\r\n\r\n| Score | What it looks like |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| **95** | Zero hedges. No restarts. Steady pacing. Clean close. The listener's takeaway is \"this person knows.\" |\r\n| **80** | One stumble, cleanly recovered. Minor hedging. Stable overall. |\r\n| **60** | 2–3 hedges. One longer pause or restart. Mostly composed but wobble visible. |\r\n| **40** | Multiple restarts. Long pauses > 3s. Over-apologizing. Topic abandonment visible. |\r\n| **20** | Cannot sustain coherent output. Multiple failed restarts, stalls, or gives up mid-rep. |\r\n\r\n## Exemplar callouts\r\n\r\n- *(positive)* \"Clean recovery at 0:22 — you paused, found the next sentence, and kept moving without losing the thread. That's composure under load.\"\r\n- *(positive)* \"Direct assertion on the main point. No 'I think' in the opening. The listener trusts you immediately.\"\r\n- *(warn)* \"The pause at 0:47 ran 3.1 seconds — listeners experience this as a stall. Next time, buy time by restating the question out loud.\"\r\n- *(warn)* \"Three 'I think' hedges in the first 20s. You had the right to state that plainly. Hedges leak confidence even when your content is strong.\"\r\n- *(critical)* \"You restarted the same sentence three times between 0:30 and 0:40. A pre-loaded framework (PREP or WSW) would give you a rail to fall back on when working memory overflows.\"\r\n\r\n## How to train confidence\r\n\r\n**Matt Abrahams' anxiety management framework, applied:**\r\n\r\n1. **Reframe** the arousal — name it as excitement, not fear (\"I'm nervous because this matters\"). Naming disarms.\r\n2. **Maximize mediocrity** — aim for B+, not A+. Perfectionism is what paralyzes you.\r\n3. **Shift your mindset** — from \"what do I want to say?\" to \"what does my audience need to hear?\"\r\n4. **Listen** — really hear the question before you start. Most confidence failures are prompt-misreads.\r\n5. **Structure** — use a framework. A pre-loaded framework is the #1 best confidence aid under pressure because it gives you a rail when working memory overflows.\r\n6. **Focus** — on the audience and the moment, not on yourself. Self-monitoring degrades performance (Beilock's choke research).\r\n\r\n**The breath tool:** slow exhales activate the parasympathetic system, lowering physiological arousal in real time. The countdown before each Cognify rep is deliberately there — that's the breath.\r\n\r\n## Common failure modes\r\n\r\n- **Hedging a claim you actually believe** — \"I think maybe we should…\" when you mean \"we should…\"\r\n- **Over-apologizing** — \"sorry, I'm going fast\" amplifies rather than hides stress\r\n- **Fighting the pause** — filling silence with \"um\" instead of thinking in silence\r\n- **Chasing a stumble** — fixating on a mistake and losing the thread\r\n- **Performing instead of thinking** — polished delivery of nothing\r\n\r\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\r\n\r\n- \"Um…\" as opener\r\n- \"Sorry, I'm going fast…\"\r\n- \"I don't know if I have a strong opinion, but…\"\r\n- \"I'm not sure, but…\"\r\n- \"Kind of, sort of, maybe, I guess…\" in the same sentence\r\n- \"Off the top of my head…\"\r\n- Ending with \"so I don't know if that answered your question\"\r\n\r\n## Frameworks that train confidence\r\n\r\n- **BLUF** (`bluf.md`) — the framework that lands fastest; fallback when you're panicking\r\n- **PREP** (`prep.md`) — Toastmasters-derived; the lightest cognitive load of any framework\r\n- **WSW** (`wsw.md`) — Matt Abrahams' recommended impromptu framework\r\n\r\n## See also\r\n\r\n- `pacing.md` — overlapping delivery dimension; low filler rate = high confidence AND high pacing\r\n- `impromptu.md` — the domain MD for when confidence stress is highest\r\n- `negotiation.md` — another domain where confidence perception determines outcomes\r\n" },
  { id: "tone", content: "# Skill: Tone\r\n\r\n> \"Vocal expressiveness — pitch variation, volume, downward inflection, presence, warmth, articulation.\"\r\n\r\nTone is the v3.0.0 dimension that captures *how the voice carries the meaning*. It's the first signal a listener's brain processes — before a single word is decoded — and it directly affects perceived credibility, authority, and trust. Same content, same structure, same thinking quality — delivered monotone or with rising statement-end pitch, it fails. A pitch-perfect explanation read with vocal flatness is a Tone failure even when everything else is on. This is the dimension most people have never deliberately trained, and one of the most measurable signals available to an audio-grading system.\r\n\r\n## Definition\r\n\r\nPitch varies intentionally across the response — not random, not flat. Statements close with downward inflection, signaling conviction. Volume rises and falls to mark important words. Vocal energy holds from first sentence to last. Articulation is crisp; consonants are formed cleanly. The listener's takeaway: *this person sounds like they mean what they're saying — and I want to keep listening*.\r\n\r\n## Why we chose this\r\n\r\nTone is the first signal a listener processes — before a single word is parsed. We chose it because monotone, upspeak, and locked-volume patterns are the most-cited reasons listeners disengage from otherwise-strong content. Measurable through pitch variation, downward inflection, and vocal-presence signals from prosody analysis. Trainable through Conviction Close and Pitch Ladder drills. Fundamental because the tone you start with sets how the listener interprets everything that follows.\r\n\r\n## Experts and sources\r\n\r\n- **Roger Love**, *Set Your Voice Free* — vocal coach to actors and CEOs; foundational on pitch range and breath support for spoken performance.\r\n- **Quantified Communications** (research firm) — empirical work on filler words, pitch variance, and persuasive impact in business presentations. Showed executives using fewer fillers were rated 33% more persuasive.\r\n- **Patsy Rodenburg**, *The Right to Speak* — the second-circle vocal presence framework used in actor training. Maps directly onto what audio listeners interpret as \"command of the room.\"\r\n- **Allan Pease**, *The Definitive Book of Body Language* — section on vocal cues; pitch variation correlates with perceived dominance and competence across cultures.\r\n- **ScienceDirect (2021)** — \"speaker confidence and accuracy are reflected in loudness, duration, and intonation; listeners decode these signals with up to 60% accuracy.\"\r\n- **Journal of Experimental Psychology / Baker & McGowan (2013)** — audiences are 30% more likely to stay engaged during presentations with vocal variety vs monotone delivery.\r\n- **Paralinguistics research on upspeak** — rising intonation at the end of statements (HRT, \"high rising terminal\") undercuts perceived authority across English-speaking populations. One of the most common and damaging vocal habits among young professionals.\r\n\r\n## What great tone sounds like\r\n\r\n- Pitch range of at least 3 semitones across a 60-second response\r\n- Statements close with downward pitch — clear conviction signal\r\n- Volume contrasts mark the most important words (\"you have *one* shot at this\")\r\n- Articulation is crisp — consonants land, no mumbling at the ends of phrases\r\n- Vocal energy holds — the last sentence is delivered with the same presence as the first\r\n- Pauses are *active* — silence after a key point lets it land instead of sounding like hesitation\r\n- Warmth comes through where the content calls for it; gravity comes through where the content calls for that\r\n\r\n## What low tone sounds like\r\n\r\n- Monotone — sustained flat pitch (low semitone variance over multiple sentences)\r\n- Upspeak — statements that rise at the end and read as questions (\"we're going to ship the feature?\")\r\n- Volume locked at one level for the entire rep — no emphasis variation\r\n- Voice tightens or thins under pressure\r\n- Mumbling — final consonants dropped, words trailing off\r\n- Breathy or breathy-quiet delivery suggesting the speaker doesn't quite believe themselves\r\n- Vocal energy fades across the response — last sentence sounds tired\r\n\r\n## Signals (hybrid, prosody-grounded)\r\n\r\nTone is the **most prosody-dependent dimension** in the rubric. Cognify's scoring pipeline grounds Tone in raw audio features extracted server-side from the rep's audio file:\r\n\r\n- **Pitch variance (std dev in semitones)** — proxy for vocal variety. Low values across multiple seconds = monotone.\r\n- **Pitch range** — peak-to-trough across the rep. Higher = more expressiveness.\r\n- **Inflection direction at sentence boundaries** — rising vs falling F0 in the last ~500ms before a sentence ends. High upspeak ratio penalizes Tone.\r\n- **Volume dynamics (RMS std dev)** — variation in vocal loudness. Locked-flat volume penalizes Tone.\r\n- **Monotone ratio** — % of speech with sustained low pitch variance.\r\n- **Articulation proxy** — consonant clarity heuristic from Deepgram word-confidence + acoustic cleanliness.\r\n\r\nWhen the prosody pipeline is offline (`prosodyAvailable: false`), Tone falls back to LLM-only scoring grounded in transcript heuristics — less accurate, clearly flagged on the rep so calibration trusts grounded scores more.\r\n\r\n## Scoring boundaries\r\n\r\n| Score | What it looks like |\r\n|---|---|\r\n| **95** | Wide intentional pitch range, every statement closes with conviction, articulation is crisp, vocal energy holds the listener through to the last word. |\r\n| **80** | Clear vocal variety, mostly downward inflection, no significant flatness moments. |\r\n| **60** | Adequate variation but flatness or one upspeak pattern shows up; articulation slips in places. |\r\n| **40** | Mostly monotone, some upspeak, voice trails at the ends of phrases. |\r\n| **20** | Sustained flat pitch, clear upspeak pattern, mumbled or breathy delivery throughout. |\r\n\r\n## Exemplar callouts\r\n\r\n- *(positive)* \"The pitch dropped on every statement close — every assertion read as a fact, not a question. That's the conviction signal that lands.\"\r\n- *(positive)* \"Volume contrast at 0:22 — you doubled the volume on 'one shot' and it pulled the listener's attention exactly where you wanted it.\"\r\n- *(warn)* \"Eight statements in a row ended with rising pitch — the upspeak pattern reads as uncertainty even when your content was confident. Land the close with a downward beat next time.\"\r\n- *(critical)* \"Pitch variance was under 1.5 semitones across 45 seconds — that's monotone territory. Listeners disengage from flat delivery faster than they disengage from weak content.\"\r\n\r\n## Common failure modes\r\n\r\n- **Monotone lock** — sustained flat pitch, especially in the second half of a response\r\n- **Upspeak** — statements that rise at the end, undercutting authority\r\n- **Volume flatness** — no emphasis variation, every word weighted the same\r\n- **Energy fade** — first sentence has presence; the last sentence trails off\r\n- **Mumbled close** — final consonants dropped, the last word doesn't land\r\n- **Breathiness under pressure** — the voice thins when stakes feel high\r\n\r\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\r\n\r\n- Statement intonation rising on declaratives\r\n- Final phrase volume dropping below the average rep volume\r\n- Pitch std dev below 1.5 semitones over any 20-second window\r\n- Words ending in vowels with no consonant articulation (\"the goal is...\" instead of \"the goal *is*\")\r\n- Run-on phrasing with no pitch resets between thoughts\r\n\r\n## How to train tone\r\n\r\nCognify trains Tone through **two surfaces**: deliberate Tone drills in Skill Lab and prosody scoring on every rep across all modes. The Tone drill bank uses prompts that demand vocal control — \"deliver this twice: first as if you're certain, then as if you're skeptical\" / \"speak this for 60 seconds with intentional pauses every 8 seconds\" / \"land the same statement three different ways: confident, doubtful, certain.\"\r\n\r\n**Real-time hints** on the start-rep page surface 1-2 sub-skill cues drawn from the user's weakest Tone sub-skill — e.g. \"land statements with downward pitch\" / \"pause two seconds after your conclusion\" / \"raise volume on the verbs that matter.\"\r\n\r\n## Frameworks that train tone\r\n\r\n- **PREP** — the impromptu framework benefits from intentional pace + pitch variation across each segment\r\n- **STAR** — narrative arc rewards vocal variety (rising tension, falling resolution)\r\n- **PPF** (Past-Present-Future) — natural pitch contour shifts between time frames\r\n\r\n## See also\r\n\r\n- `negotiation.md` — the domain where vocal presence does the most work\r\n- `tough-feedback.md` — tone under emotional weight; warmth + gravity in the same rep\r\n- `delivery.md` — adjacent dimension covering rate, pauses, and fillers; Delivery + Tone together = the full vocal picture\r\n" }
];

export const DOMAINS_BLOCKS: ReadonlyArray<{ id: string; content: string }> = [
  { id: "behavioral-interview", content: "# Domain: Behavioral Interviews\n\n\"Tell me about a time when…\" Questions asking the candidate to recount a past situation that demonstrates a competency. Used in almost every mature tech hiring process and increasingly in MBA, medical, and consulting interviews. The dominant hiring format in 2025–2026.\n\n## Why this matters for Cognify\n\nBehavioral interviews stress **structure** and **conciseness** more than any other domain. The candidate has 60–120 seconds to hit four narrative beats, include quantified results, use first-person ownership language, and map to a competency — all without notes. It is the single cleanest stress-test of live structured thinking, which is why it's a first-tier Scenario Training domain.\n\n**Preparation gap (2026 data):** 87% of companies use behavioral interviews; only **34% of candidates** arrive with structured STAR examples ready. That's a 2.5× competitive advantage available to anyone who practices.\n\n## Staple sources\n\n- **Structured behavioral interviewing methodology** — developed in the 1970s from industrial/organizational psychology research showing past behavior predicts future behavior better than situational (\"what would you do if…\") questions\n- **Amazon Leadership Principles** (16, originally 14) — the most behavioral-heavy hiring process in tech; every round includes at least one behavioral question tied to a Leadership Principle\n- **Gayle Laakmann McDowell**, *Cracking the Coding Interview* / *Cracking the PM Interview* — the definitive modern reference for tech interview prep\n- **MIT Career Advising & Professional Development** — CAPD STAR method worksheet and guide\n\n## Current practitioners (2025–2026)\n\n### Amazon interview training (most scrutinized in the industry)\n- **8–10 well-prepared stories** cover almost any behavioral question\n- Prepare **at least 2 stories per Leadership Principle** for Amazon specifically\n- Each story should map to **at least one LP**, bonus for two\n- Stories without **quantified results** are effectively disqualified at senior levels\n- **Aim for 60–120 seconds** per response — 2 minutes is the ceiling, 60s the target\n- The \"Are Right A Lot\" principle trips up candidates because they dodge the mistake question — the question is not about the mistake, it's about the **recovery and process improvement**\n\n### MIT CAPD and modern interview coaches\n- **3–5 stories minimum** per role type\n- Cover **8 core competency themes**: leadership, problem-solving, conflict, adaptability, failure, collaboration, innovation, pressure\n- \"Situation bloat\" is the #1 STAR mistake — candidates spend 90 seconds setting the scene and 10 seconds on the Action\n\n### Gayle Laakmann McDowell — CareerCup\n- First-person language is non-negotiable: switch every \"we decided\" to \"I recommended\" or \"I initiated\"\n- Specificity beats eloquence: interviewers are taking structured notes, not grading rhetoric\n- Pre-write the Result with a number before you walk into the room\n\n## The structure — STAR (see `star.md` for the framework MD)\n\n1. **Situation** — one-sentence context. Not your biography.\n2. **Task** — what *you specifically* were responsible for.\n3. **Action** — what *you personally* did. Every sentence starts with \"I\".\n4. **Result** — quantified outcome + learning layer.\n\nModern variants: **STARL** (adds Learning), **CAR** (Context-Action-Result, drops Task), **SOAR** (Situation-Obstacle-Action-Result). STAR remains dominant.\n\n## Core principles — synthesized across sources\n\n1. **First person always.** \"I\" not \"we\". Interviewers explicitly listen for ownership.\n2. **Quantified result or disqualified.** \"Approximately 30% reduction\" beats \"significant improvement.\" Reasonable estimates are fine; vague adjectives are not.\n3. **Specificity over eloquence.** A real date, a real number, a real name beats polished prose.\n4. **Tight Situation.** One sentence. The question is not about the context.\n5. **Recent is better than famous.** A story from last month beats a story from college.\n6. **Include a learning layer.** Especially for failure and conflict questions. The recovery matters more than the mistake.\n7. **Map to competency.** The best answers answer the question *and* the subtext. If they ask about conflict, the story should also show leadership and judgment.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **\"We\" instead of \"I\"** — the #1 signal interviewers flag as weak\n- **Situation bloat** — 90 seconds of scene-setting crushes the Action\n- **Vague Action** — \"we worked together and figured it out\"\n- **Missing Result numbers** — \"things got better\" is a zero\n- **No learning layer** on failure questions — dodges the actual question\n- **Reverse-chronological rambling** — starting in the middle, doubling back\n- **Leading with the Result** — that's an elevator pitch, not a STAR answer\n- **Memorized scripts that sound memorized** — interviewers pattern-match to over-preparation\n- **Generic stories reused across every question** — doesn't earn competency mapping\n\n## Exemplar phrasing\n\n> \"I was the tech lead on checkout for an ecommerce platform doing $2M/day. [**S**] During Black Friday we saw a 30% spike in abandoned carts and I was asked to diagnose within 48 hours. [**T**] I pulled the funnel data, identified that a new address validator was timing out for 15% of users, rolled back the validator behind a feature flag, and instrumented the fallback path. [**A**] Abandoned carts dropped from 30% above baseline to normal within 4 hours, recovering approximately $180K in same-day revenue. I also wrote the post-mortem and added a canary deploy gate that caught two similar issues over the next six months. [**R**]\"\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"So this is a story about the time we…\"\n- \"The team had to…\" (we-speak)\n- \"…and eventually things worked out\"\n- \"I think we ended up…\"\n- Opening without stating the situation (\"Well, I always try to…\")\n- Philosophical answers to behavioral questions (\"I think collaboration is really important because…\")\n\n## Sources\n\n- Amazon Leadership Principles and Amazon interviewing guidelines (2025–2026)\n- MIT Career Advising & Professional Development (capd.mit.edu) STAR method worksheet\n- Gayle Laakmann McDowell, *Cracking the Coding Interview* and *Cracking the PM Interview*\n- Tryexponent.com, Interview Kickstart, and IGotAnOffer 2026 Amazon behavioral interview guides\n- nSpire AI, Prachub, and Elite Resumes 2026 STAR method mastery guides\n- Industrial/organizational psychology research on structured behavioral interviewing (Janz, 1982; McDaniel et al., 1994)\n\n## See also\n\n- `star.md` — the STAR framework\n- `ppf.md` — Past → Present → Future, useful for \"tell me about yourself\" openers\n- `structure.md` — the skill dimension stressed hardest in behavioral interviews\n" },
  { id: "cold-calling", content: "# Domain: Cold Calling\n\nCold calling is B2B sales outreach where the caller has no prior relationship with the prospect. It stress-tests every communication dimension under maximum social friction: the listener did not ask for this call and is primed to end it.\n\n## Why this matters for Cognify\n\nCold calls compress an entire communication challenge into 30–45 seconds. Every word has to earn the next word. A failed opener loses the call; a rambling value statement loses the meeting. Training on cold-call scenarios forces clarity, structure, conciseness, and handling-pressure into the same rep. First-tier domain for Daily Workout and Scenario Training prompt banks.\n\n## Staple sources\n\n- **Chris Voss**, *Never Split the Difference* (2016) — tactical empathy, labeling, mirroring, calibrated questions\n- **Neil Rackham**, *SPIN Selling* (1988) — situation/problem/implication/need-payoff questioning\n- **Matthew Dixon**, *The Challenger Sale* (2011) — teach-tailor-take control\n- **Daniel Pink**, *To Sell Is Human* (2012) — attunement, buoyancy, clarity\n\n## Current practitioners (2025–2026)\n\n### Connor Murray & Eric Finch — Higher Levels\n*Connor: Enterprise AE at Datadog, ex-Oracle #1 SDR / SDR manager. Eric: strategic AE. Higher Levels' \"Cold Call Mastery\" is the modern tech-sales gold standard.*\n\n**The 3-part framework — total under 35 seconds.**\n\n1. **Opener** — assumptive formality with downward inflection.\n   > \"Hey Eric, this is Connor Murray calling from [Company]. How are you?\"\n\n2. **Value statement** — who you are, why you're calling, what you want.\n   > \"I'm part of the team that supports [industry] [role] on [domain]. We help with [priorities / pain points], typically by [outcome or transformation].\"\n   > \"I know I called you out of the blue here — just looking to set aside a time next week to get introduced and align with your priorities.\"\n\n3. **Close** — two specific time options.\n   > \"How's your calendar next week on Wednesday or Thursday?\"\n\n**Objection handling — the \"double-down\" pattern.** Acknowledge, then re-sell the meeting instead of disqualifying.\n> \"Totally get that. That's actually why I'm reaching out. We work with customers of [Competitor] all the time. This is more to get introduced and align on your priorities going forward. Would Wednesday or Thursday work?\"\n\n**Key principles:**\n- Ask twice before pivoting to follow-up questions\n- Prepare 3–5 objection flashcards and memorize responses\n- Send the agenda invite live, mid-call, and confirm delivery: \"I just sent the invite — mind checking that it went through?\"\n\n### Armand Farrokh & Nick Cegelski — 30 Minutes to President's Club\n*Co-hosts of the 30MPC podcast, authors of* Cold Calling Sucks (And That's Why It Works) *(2024). Armand: VP Sales at 29, ex-Pave, ex-Carta. Nick: 3× top enterprise seller.*\n\n**Signature moves:**\n- **\"Heard the name tossed around\"** opener — leads with context/familiarity instead of permission begging\n- **Problem proposition** — lead with a vivid, emotionally-charged problem the buyer actually feels, *then* briefly show how you solve it\n- **\"Speak in dumb human language\"** — kill marketing jargon, talk like a real person\n- **Mr. Miyagi objection handling** — absorb the objection instead of fighting it\n\n### Chris Orlob — pclub.io\n*Co-founder of pclub.io. Helped grow Gong from $200K → $200M+ ARR. Trained 11,000+ sales professionals. Specializes in enterprise / C-suite selling.*\n\n**Core teaching:**\n- **A C-suite meeting is not a discovery call.** \"Unless the exec came inbound, your meeting shouldn't focus on discovery — by the time you reach the C-suite, you should have done plenty of discovery already.\"\n- Share insights and POVs with well-crafted questions, not discovery questions\n- **\"90% of sellers can't sell to the C-suite\"** — that's the skill gap in enterprise\n\n### Josh Braun — Badass B2B\n*Cold outreach coach. Anti-\"commission breath\" methodology — prospects feel safe telling you the truth because they don't feel sold.*\n\n**Opener pattern:**\n> \"Hi I'm Josh. I was hoping you could help me out for a moment.\"\n\n## Gong Labs data — 2025 findings\n\n- Asking **11–14 questions** per call correlates with **70%+** cold-call success\n- Persistence: **39%** connect rate on first attempt → **93%** by the third\n- Stating the reason for your call makes cold calls **2.1×** more successful\n- Asking how the buyer has been performs **6.6×** better\n- Talk-to-listen ratio on successful cold calls: **55:45** (cold calls are different from discovery — you're there to educate, not ask)\n- **\"Did I catch you at a bad time?\"** makes you **40% less likely** to book a meeting\n- Average rep sends **344 cold emails** per meeting booked (phone compounds this)\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Permission begging** — \"Is now a bad time?\" / \"Do you have a quick minute?\"\n- **Marketing jargon** — \"best-of-breed end-to-end AI-powered solution\"\n- **Leading with the product** instead of the problem\n- **Pitch longer than 45 seconds** — prospect has already decided\n- **Pivoting to discovery too early** — the prospect is not on a discovery call yet\n- **Disqualifying at first objection** — objection ≠ rejection\n- **Vague close** — \"maybe sometime next week?\"\n\n## Exemplar phrasings (what high-scoring reps sound like)\n\n- **Strong opener**: \"Hey [Name], this is [Your Name] from [Company]. Quick reason for the call — I noticed [specific trigger], and I help [role] with [specific problem]. Worth a quick intro Tuesday or Thursday?\"\n- **Problem proposition**: \"Most [role] I talk to lose an hour a day on [specific pain]. We cut that to zero.\"\n- **Double-down objection response**: \"Totally get it. That's actually why I called — [specific reason that reframes the objection].\"\n- **Specific close**: \"Wednesday at 2 or Thursday at 10?\"\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"Hi, I know you're busy so I'll be quick…\"\n- \"I was wondering if I could take 15 minutes of your time to introduce our best-in-class platform…\"\n- \"We're a cloud-based end-to-end AI-powered…\"\n- \"Do you have a moment?\"\n- \"Is this a bad time?\"\n\n## Sources\n\n- Connor Murray & Eric Finch, *Cold Call Mastery* and *Cold Call Framework 2025* — Higher Levels\n- Armand Farrokh & Nick Cegelski, *Cold Calling Sucks (And That's Why It Works)* — 30MPC (2024)\n- Chris Orlob, pclub.io training and LinkedIn commentary (2025–2026)\n- Josh Braun, *The Badass B2B Growth Guide*\n- Gong Labs, *The Best Sales Insights of 2025* and the cold-call data series\n- Chris Voss, *Never Split the Difference* (2016)\n" },
  { id: "exec-briefing", content: "# Domain: Executive Briefings & Presentations\n\nCommunicating with senior leaders — C-suite, VPs, board members — under time pressure and with high stakes. Every word competes for attention from someone whose calendar is priced by the minute. Gets the main point across fast, earns the right to the detail, and makes the listener smarter rather than just informed.\n\n## Why this matters for Cognify\n\nExec briefings stress **structure**, **clarity**, and **tone** above all. The listener won't follow a long build-up, won't tolerate hedging, and expects the speaker to have already done the discovery work. Cognify's Daily Workout and Scenario Training prompt banks use exec-briefing contexts heavily because they force the speaker to *lead with the answer* rather than *explain to it*.\n\n## Staple sources\n\n- **Barbara Minto**, *The Pyramid Principle* (1987) — answer-first executive communication (see `scqa.md`, `minto.md`)\n- **Nancy Duarte**, *Resonate* (2010), *Slide:ology* (2008), *Illuminate* (2016)\n- **Jerry Weissman**, *Presenting to Win* (2003 / 2011) — 20 years coaching Silicon Valley IPO roadshows at Cisco, Yahoo, Microsoft\n- **Carmine Gallo**, *Talk Like TED* (2014), *The Presentation Secrets of Steve Jobs* (2009)\n- **Chris Anderson**, *TED Talks: The Official TED Guide to Public Speaking* (2016)\n- **The Heath Brothers**, *Made to Stick* (2007) — the SUCCES principles (Simple, Unexpected, Concrete, Credible, Emotional, Stories)\n\n## Current practitioners (2025–2026)\n\n### Nancy Duarte — Duarte Inc.\n*Presentation design firm, clients include Apple, Google, Cisco, TED. Longest-running expert in the exec-communication space.*\n\n**Signature principle — the contrast Sparkline:** Great presentations alternate between \"what is\" (the status quo) and \"what could be\" (the new vision), ending in a call to action. The gap between them should be as big as possible — the rest of the presentation bridges that gap.\n\n**STAR moments:** \"Something They'll Always Remember.\" Build at least one intentional memory peak into every high-stakes presentation — a surprising stat, a physical demo, a repeatable phrase.\n\n**Audience-first:** \"Persuasion doesn't start with you and your message — it starts with your audience.\" The first move is understanding what they care about, not what you want to say.\n\n### Jerry Weissman — Power Presentations\n*20+ years coaching executives on their highest-stakes moments. Trained Cisco's founders for the IPO roadshow that built a $600B market cap. Author of 75 techniques for executive presentations.*\n\n**WIIFY — \"What's In It For You?\"** Every presentation opens with the audience's answer, not the speaker's intro. If the first 30 seconds don't make the listener care, the rest doesn't matter.\n\n**Verbal links** — explicit signposting between points (\"The second reason I believe this…\", \"Which brings us to…\") so the listener never has to reconstruct the argument structure.\n\n**ERA body language** — Eye connect, Reach out, Animation. Applies to live delivery; adapts partially to voice-only training.\n\n### Chris Orlob — pclub.io (C-suite selling focus)\n*Helped grow Gong from $200K → $200M+ ARR. Specializes in enterprise / C-suite communication.*\n\n**Core teaching — the C-suite inversion:**\n- \"A C-suite meeting is not a discovery call\" (unless the exec came inbound)\n- By the time you reach the C-suite, discovery should already be done\n- Share **insights and POVs** with well-crafted questions, not discovery questions\n- **\"90% of sellers can't sell to the C-suite\"** — the skill gap is enormous\n\n### Carmine Gallo — communication coach, Forbes/Harvard Business Review\n*Author of* Talk Like TED *and* The Presentation Secrets of Steve Jobs. *Analyzed 500+ TED talks to extract delivery patterns.*\n\n**The 18-minute rule** — borrowed from TED. Beyond 18 minutes, cognitive load degrades sharply. Exec briefings should be *far* shorter — 5 minutes is the working ceiling; 60 seconds is the real skill.\n\n**Three-act structure** — beginning (hook + promise), middle (supporting points, max 3), end (call to action + memorable line).\n\n## Core principles — synthesized across sources\n\n1. **Answer first.** Minto, Weissman, Orlob, and every modern practitioner agree. Don't build to the conclusion — start with it, then justify.\n2. **One big idea.** Chris Anderson's \"through-line.\" If you can't state the presentation in one sentence, it isn't ready.\n3. **3–5 supporting points, max.** Beyond five, retention collapses. Beyond three, executives stop tracking.\n4. **Quantified results, not adjectives.** \"Significant improvement\" is invisible. \"Cut onboarding from 7 months to 3\" is memorable.\n5. **Audience-centric opening.** WIIFY, not \"let me walk you through what we've been working on.\"\n6. **Anticipate the objection.** Great execs will challenge the claim — have the defense already loaded.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Preamble and throat-clearing** — \"So, um, I just wanted to share a quick update on…\"\n- **Chronological structure** — telling the story in the order it happened instead of in order of importance\n- **Data dump without interpretation** — \"here are the numbers\" without \"here's what they mean\"\n- **Burying the ask** — not stating explicitly what you need from the room\n- **Hedging** — \"we think maybe we should consider potentially…\"\n- **Marketing adjectives** — \"world-class\", \"leading\", \"best-in-class\", \"game-changing\"\n- **Missing the through-line** — jumping between unrelated points with no frame\n\n## Exemplar phrasings\n\n- **WIIFY opener**: \"I'm here because we have a shot at cutting enterprise-sales ramp time from seven months to three — and I need your help with one decision to make that real.\"\n- **Answer-first**: \"We should build a 30-day scenario bootcamp for new AEs. Three reasons. First…\"\n- **Quantified close**: \"If we approve this in the next two weeks, new reps hired in Q3 hit quota in January instead of May. That's $2.1M in pipeline we don't currently have.\"\n- **Verbal link**: \"That's the *what*. Here's the *how*.\"\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"I'd like to walk you through…\"\n- \"Just wanted to share…\"\n- \"Before I dive in, a little background…\"\n- \"Let me take a step back…\"\n- \"At a high level…\"\n- Opening with your name and team (the exec already has the calendar invite)\n\n## Sources\n\n- Nancy Duarte, *Resonate* (2010); Duarte Inc. blog (2025)\n- Jerry Weissman, *Presenting to Win* (2003/2011)\n- Chris Orlob, pclub.io C-suite training and LinkedIn commentary (2025–2026)\n- Carmine Gallo, *Talk Like TED* (2014); *The Presentation Secrets of Steve Jobs* (2009)\n- Chris Anderson, *TED Talks* (2016)\n- Barbara Minto, *The Pyramid Principle* (1987)\n- Heath Brothers, *Made to Stick* (2007)\n" },
  { id: "impromptu", content: "# Domain: Impromptu Speaking & Thinking on Your Feet\n\nSpeaking when you didn't know you'd be speaking. The hallway question, the meeting follow-up, the interview curveball, the toast you weren't told you'd give. Impromptu speaking is the purest test of structured thinking under pressure — you can't memorize, you can't rehearse, and the listener is evaluating you in real time.\n\n## Why this matters for Cognify\n\nImpromptu is the dimension David (ex-IBM / Watson) explicitly flagged as under-trained in the April 2026 advisory meeting: *\"the gap in training on how to deliver communication effectively rather than just what to say.\"* Cognify's Daily Workout is fundamentally an impromptu gym — every rep is a prompt the user has never seen before, with no preparation time. This domain is load-bearing for the entire product.\n\nStresses all six dimensions but especially **thinking on the spot**, **structure**, and **handling pressure**.\n\n## Staple sources\n\n- **Toastmasters International** — Table Topics impromptu methodology since the 1950s (see `prep.md`)\n- **Dale Carnegie**, *How to Develop Self-Confidence & Influence People by Public Speaking* (1926) — the original\n- **Scott Berkun**, *Confessions of a Public Speaker* (2009) — honest, practical, anti-polish\n- **Aristotle**, *Rhetoric* (c. 350 BCE) — ethos/pathos/logos, the first framework for making a point fast\n\n## Current practitioners (2020–2026)\n\n### Matt Abrahams — Stanford Graduate School of Business\n*Lecturer at Stanford GSB. Host of the* Think Fast, Talk Smart *podcast (one of the most-downloaded business podcasts globally). Author of* Think Faster, Talk Smarter *(2023).*\n\nThis is the modern definitive work on impromptu speaking. Abrahams' framework is science-based, built from IO psych research on speaking anxiety, working memory, and audience attention.\n\n**The Six-Step Methodology for Speaking Spontaneously:**\n\n1. **Manage anxiety** — reframe physiological arousal as excitement, not fear. Name it out loud (\"I'm nervous because this matters\") to disarm it.\n2. **Maximize mediocrity** — aim for \"good enough,\" not perfect. The pursuit of perfection is what paralyzes you. B+ beats A- that never happens.\n3. **Shift your mindset** — from \"what do I want to say?\" to \"what does my audience need to hear?\"\n4. **Listen** — really hear the question or the room before you start. Most spontaneous-speaking failures are misreadings of what was actually asked.\n5. **Structure** — use a framework. Any framework. The list below.\n6. **Focus** — on the audience and the moment, not on yourself. Self-monitoring degrades performance.\n\n**The frameworks Abrahams teaches for impromptu:**\n\n- **What? → So what? → Now what?** — (see `wsw.md`) — the default for \"what do you think about X?\"\n- **Problem → Solution → Benefit** — for recommendation questions\n- **Position → Action → Benefit** — a tighter variant of PSPA\n- **PREP** — Point → Reason → Example → Point (see `prep.md`) — Toastmasters-derived\n- **Past → Present → Future** — (see `ppf.md`) — for \"tell me about yourself\" and introductions\n\n**The Mindset Shift:** *\"We start by saying, 'here's what I want to say,' versus, 'what does the audience or person I'm speaking to need to hear.' That's a fundamental mind shift. If I don't understand from your perspective what's important for you, what knowledge you have now versus where I would like you to be, I can't tailor my message.\"*\n\n### Toastmasters International — Table Topics\n*The single most-practiced impromptu-speaking training globally. In every weekly Toastmasters meeting, members are given a random topic and must speak on it for 1–2 minutes with no preparation.*\n\n**The Table Topics discipline:**\n- 1-2 minutes maximum\n- No notes\n- Must have a beginning, middle, and end\n- Scored on structure and clarity, not polish\n- Weekly practice — the volume is the point\n\nThe PREP framework (`prep.md`) is the Toastmasters default for Table Topics because it's the easiest to hold in working memory under stress.\n\n## Core principles — synthesized across sources\n\n1. **A framework in your head beats a blank mind.** The single best impromptu prep is memorizing 2–3 frameworks so well that one loads automatically when you hear the question.\n2. **Buy 3 seconds.** Restate the question (\"So you're asking whether X\"), name a value (\"what I think matters most here is…\"), or acknowledge tension (\"that's a question with two real answers\"). These are thinking-time moves that don't sound like stalling.\n3. **Structure beats content.** A B+ answer with a clear framework beats an A+ answer that rambles. Listeners remember structure.\n4. **Listen for the real question.** Most impromptu failures are answers to the wrong question. Before answering, briefly confirm what's being asked.\n5. **Manage anxiety by naming it.** Anxiety suppressed grows; anxiety named shrinks. \"This matters to me so I'm nervous\" is a disarming opener.\n6. **End on time.** Trailing off is the #1 way to undo a great opening. Land the ending cleanly, even if you have to cut the middle.\n7. **Every framework has a restate.** PREP ends with Point, WSW with Now What, PPF with Future. Without a restate, impromptu answers feel unfinished.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Blank start** — silence or \"um\" while working memory catches up\n- **No structure** — answering in whatever order things come to mind\n- **Forgetting the question** — ending on a different topic than the one asked\n- **Over-committing to the first sentence** — saying something you can't support\n- **Hedging to protect yourself** — \"I don't know if I have a strong opinion…\"\n- **Trailing off** — no planned ending, so the answer dribbles to a stop\n- **Answering the wrong question** — misreading what was actually asked\n- **Performing instead of thinking** — polished delivery of nothing\n- **Over-apologizing** — \"sorry, I'm not sure…\" kills listener confidence before content arrives\n\n## Exemplar phrasings\n\n- **Restate + frame:** \"That's really a question about [X]. Let me give you the shortest useful answer I have.\"\n- **Buy time honestly:** \"Give me five seconds to think about that in a useful way.\"\n- **Name the tension:** \"There's a real tradeoff here. Let me give you both sides, then my take.\"\n- **Clean close:** \"So — [restate the point]. That's my answer.\"\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"That's a great question…\" (buys no time and sounds practiced)\n- \"I mean…\" (the #1 impromptu tell)\n- \"Kind of, sort of, maybe, I guess…\"\n- \"I don't really know…\"\n- \"Off the top of my head…\" (permission to be sloppy)\n- \"Anyways\" as a transition\n- Ending with \"so yeah\"\n\n## Sources\n\n- Matt Abrahams, *Think Faster, Talk Smarter: How to Speak Successfully When You're Put on the Spot* (Simon & Schuster, 2023)\n- Matt Abrahams, *Think Fast, Talk Smart* podcast (Stanford GSB, 2020–)\n- Toastmasters International Table Topics methodology\n- Dale Carnegie, *The Quick and Easy Way to Effective Speaking* (1962 edition)\n- Scott Berkun, *Confessions of a Public Speaker* (2009)\n- Aristotle, *Rhetoric* (c. 350 BCE)\n\n## See also\n\n- `prep.md` — the Toastmasters default impromptu framework\n- `wsw.md` — What → So What → Now What, Abrahams' default recommendation\n- `ppf.md` — Past → Present → Future, for introductions\n- `thinking-on-the-spot.md` — the skill dimension stressed hardest here\n- `handling-pressure.md` — the other skill that impromptu training develops\n" },
  { id: "negotiation", content: "# Domain: Negotiation & Persuasion Under Pressure\n\nGetting to an agreement when the other party starts from a different position — salary talks, deal terms, scope fights, stakeholder disagreements, any moment where both sides are advocating and the outcome is contested. The sub-domain of communication where every word has to carry weight and every pause is a tactical choice.\n\n## Why this matters for Cognify\n\nNegotiation stresses **tone**, **handling pressure**, and **thinking on the spot** more than any other domain. It is the purest test of listening-under-fire — the speaker has to hear what the other person is *actually* saying (not what they expected to hear), adjust mid-sentence, and deliver a response that moves the conversation without escalating it. Cognify trains negotiation scenarios because they reveal in 60 seconds what most people struggle with for an entire career.\n\n## Staple sources\n\n- **Roger Fisher, William Ury, Bruce Patton**, *Getting to Yes* (1981) — Harvard Negotiation Project; the principled-negotiation framework (interests not positions)\n- **William Ury**, *Getting Past No* (1991) and *Possible* (2024) — the breakthrough-negotiation methodology\n- **Deepak Malhotra & Max Bazerman**, *Negotiation Genius* (2007) — Harvard Business School research-backed techniques\n- **Robert Cialdini**, *Influence* (1984) / *Pre-Suasion* (2016) — six universal principles of persuasion (reciprocity, commitment, social proof, authority, liking, scarcity)\n- **Herb Cohen**, *You Can Negotiate Anything* (1980) — time, information, power; the three negotiation levers\n\n## Current practitioners (2016–2026)\n\n### Chris Voss — The Black Swan Group\n*Former FBI lead international kidnapping negotiator. Author of* Never Split the Difference *(2016), the most-cited modern negotiation book. His techniques come from real hostage cases, not business-school simulations.*\n\n**Tactical Empathy.** The core concept. *\"Understanding the feelings and mindset of another in the moment and also hearing what is behind those feelings.\"* This is not sympathy. It is disciplined attention to what the other side is feeling, said out loud, to build trust and lower defensiveness.\n\n**Labeling.** Name the emotion the other side is having before they have to say it. *\"It sounds like you're worried about…\"*, *\"It seems like this is more about X than Y.\"* Labels disarm because they make the other person feel heard.\n\n**Mirroring.** Repeat the last 3 words (or the critical 1–3 words) they just said, as a question. This prompts them to elaborate without feeling interrogated. *\"Forty thousand?\"* invites detail the way *\"Why forty thousand?\"* never could.\n\n**Calibrated questions.** Open-ended questions beginning with \"What\" or \"How.\" *\"How am I supposed to do that?\"* / *\"What about this works for you?\"* Calibrated questions force the other side to solve the problem, while *creating the illusion of control* for them. Voss: *\"When you ask questions that force others to think and solve, they feel in control, even if you're steering.\"*\n\n**\"That's right.\"** The target response. \"That's right\" means the other side feels completely understood. *Different from* \"you're right,\" which means they're trying to end the conversation. \"That's right\" is a negotiation breakthrough; \"you're right\" is a stall.\n\n**Avoid \"yes.\" Aim for \"no.\"** Counter-intuitive. Early \"yes\" is cheap and often hollow. \"No\" gives the other side a feeling of safety and control, which paradoxically opens them up. Voss: *\"No is the start of the negotiation, not the end.\"*\n\n**2024 Forrester study** — mid-market companies using tactical empathy and calibrated questions in their sales approach saw a **22% improvement in quota attainment** within 6 months.\n\n### William Ury — Harvard Negotiation Project\n*Co-author of* Getting to Yes *(1981). Released* Possible *in 2024, his first major book in over a decade — applies the breakthrough-negotiation method to polarized, high-conflict situations.*\n\n**Principled negotiation** (from *Getting to Yes*):\n1. **Separate people from the problem** — attack the issue, not the counterpart\n2. **Focus on interests, not positions** — ask \"why do you want that?\" rather than \"what do you want?\"\n3. **Invent options for mutual gain** — brainstorm before choosing\n4. **Insist on objective criteria** — market rate, precedent, expert opinion\n\n**BATNA** (Best Alternative To a Negotiated Agreement) — Fisher/Ury's most durable contribution. Always know your walk-away before the negotiation starts. The negotiator with the stronger BATNA has the leverage.\n\n### Deepak Malhotra — Harvard Business School\n*Professor at HBS. Author of* Negotiation Genius *(2007) and* Negotiating the Impossible *(2016). Has trained Fortune 100 CEOs and government negotiators.*\n\n**Three Ps of impossible negotiations:** Power (process), Pictures (framing), Procedure (managing the path). The deepest of these is *framing* — who controls how the problem is described controls which solutions feel reasonable.\n\n**Ask questions before making offers.** The negotiator who speaks first often anchors badly. Malhotra's research: in 70% of negotiations, the second-mover wins.\n\n## Core principles — synthesized across sources\n\n1. **Listen before you solve.** The single biggest error in negotiation is proposing before understanding.\n2. **Separate people from problem.** Attack the issue, not the counterpart.\n3. **Label the emotion in the room.** Unacknowledged emotion escalates; named emotion shrinks.\n4. **Ask calibrated questions.** Open-ended, \"How\" and \"What,\" forcing the other side to engage.\n5. **Know your BATNA.** Never negotiate without knowing your walk-away.\n6. **Silence is a tool.** After you make an offer or ask a question, stop talking. The listener will fill the space, and what they say is information.\n7. **\"No\" is the start, not the end.** Early \"no\" is a gift — it gives you real information to work with.\n8. **Anchor, but earn the right.** Anchoring early with weak credibility backfires. Anchoring after establishing legitimacy works.\n9. **Never split the difference.** 50/50 is the failure mode of lazy negotiators — always ask \"what would make this work for both of us?\"\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Racing to solve** — pitching your solution before understanding their interest\n- **Taking positions personally** — arguing the person instead of the problem\n- **Escalating language** — \"fine, I'll just…\", \"you're being unreasonable\"\n- **Over-explaining** — giving justifications no one asked for (weakens your position)\n- **Early capitulation** — accepting the first reasonable offer instead of testing it\n- **Ignoring emotion** — pretending the room is rational when it isn't\n- **Missing the second-mover advantage** — rushing to make the first offer\n- **Talking through silence** — filling the other party's thinking time with more words\n\n## Exemplar phrasings\n\n- **Label:** \"It sounds like this timeline is more important to you than the price.\"\n- **Mirror:** *[They say \"the quarterly budget is tight\"]* — *\"Tight?\"*\n- **Calibrated question:** \"How am I supposed to make that work on my side?\"\n- **Reframe:** \"If we set aside the number for a moment, what would a great outcome look like for your team?\"\n- **Silent pause:** *(after their offer)* \"Hmm.\" *(then wait)*\n- **Going no:** \"It seems like now isn't the right moment for this.\" *(Voss's deliberate induced-no move)*\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"I need…\" (positions, not interests)\n- \"That's unreasonable.\"\n- \"You're wrong because…\"\n- \"Can we just split the difference?\"\n- \"Take it or leave it.\"\n- \"I hear what you're saying, but…\" (negates the acknowledgment)\n- \"Trust me…\"\n- Over-justifying the ask (\"I only want this because…\")\n\n## Sources\n\n- Chris Voss, *Never Split the Difference* (2016); Black Swan Group training (2025)\n- Roger Fisher, William Ury, Bruce Patton, *Getting to Yes* (1981, 2011 update)\n- William Ury, *Possible* (2024)\n- Deepak Malhotra & Max Bazerman, *Negotiation Genius* (2007)\n- Robert Cialdini, *Influence* (1984); *Pre-Suasion* (2016)\n- 2024 Forrester Consulting study on tactical empathy in B2B sales\n\n## See also\n\n- `cold-calling.md` — the domain where tactical empathy and calibrated questions are used most aggressively\n- `tough-feedback.md` — overlapping emotional-pressure domain\n- `tone.md` — the skill dimension most stressed by negotiation\n" },
  { id: "storytelling", content: "# Domain: Storytelling & Public Speaking\n\nCommunicating an idea to an audience through narrative rather than recitation. Every great keynote, TED talk, pitch, and memorable meeting opener is built on the same mechanics: a hook that earns attention, a structure that sustains it, and a specific human moment that makes the idea stick. This is what separates \"informing\" from \"moving.\"\n\n## Why this matters for Cognify\n\nStorytelling stresses **structure**, **tone**, and **handling pressure** under the specific constraint that the speaker has to hold the listener's attention without interrupting to check if it's working. Cognify uses storytelling scenarios to train the hardest form of structure — one where the framework is invisible to the audience but load-bearing for the speaker.\n\n## Staple sources\n\n- **Robert McKee**, *Story* (1997) — the screenwriting bible; used by Pixar and Netflix story rooms. Substance, structure, style, principles.\n- **Chip Heath & Dan Heath**, *Made to Stick* (2007) — the SUCCES principles: Simple, Unexpected, Concrete, Credible, Emotional, Stories\n- **Nancy Duarte**, *Resonate* (2010) — the contrast sparkline, alternating between \"what is\" and \"what could be\"\n- **Joseph Campbell**, *The Hero with a Thousand Faces* (1949) — monomyth, the underlying shape of nearly every told story\n- **Aristotle**, *Poetics* (c. 335 BCE) — ethos, pathos, logos; the original three-act structure\n\n## Current practitioners (2020–2026)\n\n### Chris Anderson — TED\n*Curator of TED since 2001. Author of* TED Talks: The Official TED Guide to Public Speaking *(2016). Has hosted or edited more TED talks than any living human.*\n\n**The Through-Line Principle.** Every great talk has exactly one idea — one \"through-line\" — that every other piece of the talk serves. If you can't state the talk in a single sentence, it isn't ready. Anderson: \"A through-line is like a strong cord or rope on which you will attach all the elements of your talk.\"\n\n**The 18-minute cognitive limit.** TED talks cap at 18 minutes because attention degrades sharply beyond that. Anderson argues 18 minutes is \"long enough to be serious and short enough to hold people's attention,\" and it forces merciless pruning.\n\n**Four approaches to the idea:** connection (build the personal bridge), narration (tell the story), explanation (build the mental model), persuasion (rearrange the audience's thinking). Every TED talk uses at least one.\n\n### Carmine Gallo — communications coach\n*Analyzed 500+ TED talks for* Talk Like TED *(2014). Follow-up books:* The Storyteller's Secret, The Bezos Blueprint.\n\n**The Nine Principles of great TED talks:** Passion, Storytelling, Practice, the Rule of Three, Making the Audience Care, Authenticity, Visual Aids, Brevity, Enjoyment.\n\n**Three types of stories a speaker can use:**\n1. Personal stories — the most powerful; build neural coupling between speaker and listener\n2. Stories about other people — useful when personal stories would feel narcissistic\n3. Stories about brands or products — weakest, and nearly always replaceable by a better type\n\n**\"The human brain loves novelty.\"** An unfamiliar, unusual, or unexpected element in a presentation intrigues the audience and jolts them out of their preconceived notions.\n\n**The Rule of Three.** Audiences retain three items at a time under cognitive load. Not four, not five. Three.\n\n### Nancy Duarte — Duarte Inc.\n*See also `exec-briefing.md` for her broader framework.*\n\n**The Contrast Sparkline.** Great presentations and stories alternate between \"what is\" (the status quo) and \"what could be\" (the vision). The gap between them is the engine — the wider the gap, the more the audience cares.\n\n**STAR moments** — \"Something They'll Always Remember.\" Build at least one intentional peak into every talk: a surprising stat, a physical demo, a vulnerable personal moment, a repeatable phrase. Duarte's research: without a STAR moment, 90% of presentations are forgotten within 24 hours.\n\n### Brené Brown — researcher / speaker\n*Author of* Daring Greatly, Braving the Wilderness, Dare to Lead. *Her 2010 TEDx Houston talk on vulnerability is one of the most-watched TED talks of all time.*\n\n**Vulnerability as narrative anchor.** Brown's research and speaking practice both show that listeners bond with speakers who risk being wrong, afraid, or uncertain on stage. Polished invulnerable delivery creates distance; vulnerability closes it. The risk has to be genuine — performed vulnerability registers as manipulation.\n\n## Core principles — synthesized across sources\n\n1. **One idea.** If the talk is about more than one thing, it's not ready.\n2. **Start with the audience, not yourself.** WIIFY (What's In It For You) — not \"let me tell you about what I've been working on.\"\n3. **Contrast is the engine.** \"What is\" vs \"what could be.\" Status quo vs vision. Problem vs solution. Without contrast, there's no story.\n4. **Specific beats general.** One named person in one named moment beats a thousand statistics. Then pair the specific with the general.\n5. **Emotion before logic, then logic.** The audience has to *feel* the point before they're ready to *think* it.\n6. **Rehearse the opening and the closing.** The middle can be improvised. The first 30 seconds and the last 30 seconds can't.\n7. **The rule of three.** Three supporting points, max. Three examples, max. Three memorable lines, max.\n8. **Build in a STAR moment.** At least one peak the audience will still remember tomorrow.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Multiple through-lines** — the talk is about \"innovation and culture and leadership\" instead of one specific claim\n- **No hook** — starting with \"Hi, my name is…\" instead of a compelling opening\n- **Abstract opening** — talking about \"the importance of communication\" when you should be telling a 20-second story\n- **Over-prepared delivery** — memorized to the point of sounding robotic\n- **Ignoring the audience** — same talk, same slides, regardless of who's in the room\n- **No emotional peak** — all logic, no human moment\n- **Weak ending** — trailing off with \"so… yeah, that's what I wanted to share\"\n- **Data without interpretation** — showing a chart without telling the audience what it means\n\n## Exemplar phrasings\n\n- **Hook openings:**\n  - \"Eight months ago I watched a friend die because his ICU nurse couldn't explain something to the attending physician clearly enough.\"\n  - \"Every morning 4 million Americans wake up and do something their grandparents would have called impossible.\"\n  - \"This is a story about a Tuesday I will never forget.\"\n- **Contrast frame:** \"Today, [X is true and broken]. Imagine instead [Y — specific, concrete, achievable].\"\n- **The ask close:** \"If you take one thing from this: [specific repeatable line]. And tomorrow morning, do [one specific action].\"\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"Hi, my name is…\" as the opening line\n- \"Today I'm going to talk about…\"\n- \"Let me start with a little background…\"\n- \"In conclusion…\" (as the actual transition to the conclusion)\n- \"I'd like to thank you for having me…\" as the close\n- \"So… yeah\" as the close\n- Using phrases like \"amazing\", \"incredible\", \"game-changing\" without the example to earn them\n\n## Sources\n\n- Chris Anderson, *TED Talks: The Official TED Guide to Public Speaking* (2016)\n- Carmine Gallo, *Talk Like TED* (2014); *The Storyteller's Secret* (2016); *The Bezos Blueprint* (2022)\n- Nancy Duarte, *Resonate* (2010); Duarte Inc. blog (2025)\n- Chip Heath & Dan Heath, *Made to Stick* (2007)\n- Robert McKee, *Story* (1997)\n- Brené Brown, *Dare to Lead* (2018); TEDx Houston (2010)\n- Joseph Campbell, *The Hero with a Thousand Faces* (1949)\n\n## See also\n\n- `exec-briefing.md` — the overlapping domain for executive-audience storytelling\n- `ppf.md` — Past → Present → Future, the narrative opener framework\n- `aida.md` — Attention → Interest → Desire → Action, for persuasive storytelling\n" },
  { id: "tough-feedback", content: "# Domain: Tough Feedback & Performance Conversations\n\nGiving corrective or critical feedback to a peer, report, or manager in a way that actually lands — without triggering defensiveness, damaging the relationship, or softening the message into uselessness. The hardest routine communication most professionals ever do.\n\n## Why this matters for Cognify\n\nFeedback conversations stress **clarity**, **structure**, **tone**, and **handling pressure** simultaneously. They demand specificity under emotional weight — the speaker has to be concrete enough to be actionable while warm enough to preserve the relationship. Cognify's Scenario Training mode treats feedback delivery as a first-tier domain because it is the rep most professionals avoid practicing and most need to get right.\n\n## Staple sources\n\n- **Kim Scott**, *Radical Candor* (2017) — Care Personally + Challenge Directly (see current practitioners below)\n- **Douglas Stone & Sheila Heen**, *Thanks for the Feedback* (2014) — the receiver side; three feedback triggers\n- **Kerry Patterson, Joseph Grenny, Ron McMillan, Al Switzler**, *Crucial Conversations* (2002, updated 2022) — STATE your path\n- **Marshall Goldsmith**, *What Got You Here Won't Get You There* (2007) — feedforward, stakeholder-centered coaching\n- **Center for Creative Leadership**, Situation-Behavior-Impact (SBI) model — 1990s (see `bie.md`)\n\n## Current practitioners (2020–2026)\n\n### Kim Scott — Radical Candor\n*Former Google and Apple executive. Her framework has become the default vocabulary for modern feedback conversations.*\n\n**The Radical Candor 2×2:**\n\n```\n                 Care Personally →\n                 LOW          HIGH\nChallenge       ─────────────────────\nDirectly        │ Obnoxious │ Radical │\n↑ HIGH          │ Aggression│  Candor │\n                ├───────────┼─────────┤\n                │Manipulative│Ruinous │\n  LOW           │ Insincerity│ Empathy│\n                └───────────┴─────────┘\n```\n\nFour quadrants:\n- **Radical Candor** (target): high care + high challenge — specific and sincere praise, kind and clear criticism\n- **Ruinous Empathy**: caring so much about not hurting feelings that you withhold information the person needs — the most common failure mode among new managers\n- **Obnoxious Aggression**: challenging directly without showing care — \"brilliant jerk\" territory, destroys trust\n- **Manipulative Insincerity**: neither caring nor challenging — politics and passive-aggression\n\n**Principles:**\n- **Solicit first, then give.** Ask for feedback before giving it; models vulnerability and earns permission.\n- **Praise in public, criticize in private.** Public praise reinforces and builds safety; private criticism preserves dignity.\n- **Be specific and sincere.** Generic praise (\"great job!\") rings hollow; generic criticism (\"you need to improve\") is not actionable.\n- **Give it quickly.** Waiting weeks turns a small fixable moment into a performance issue.\n\n### Douglas Stone & Sheila Heen — Harvard Negotiation Project\n*Authors of* Thanks for the Feedback. *Focus on the receiver side of feedback — what makes it possible to hear it.*\n\n**The three triggers that shut down feedback reception:**\n\n1. **Truth triggers** — \"That's not accurate\" / \"That's not fair.\" Receiver rejects the content.\n2. **Relationship triggers** — \"I can't believe *you* of all people are telling me this.\" Receiver rejects the giver.\n3. **Identity triggers** — \"This means I'm a bad person / a failure / not who I thought I was.\" Receiver rejects the implication.\n\nWhen giving feedback, anticipate which trigger is likely — and structure the delivery to defuse it before it fires.\n\n### Marshall Goldsmith — executive coaching\n*Coached 150+ Fortune 500 CEOs. Pioneered \"feedforward.\"*\n\n**Feedforward instead of feedback:** Ask the person what they'd like to improve, then give concrete suggestions for *the future* rather than critiquing *the past*. Past-focused feedback triggers defense; future-focused suggestions trigger exploration. Does not replace corrective feedback but complements it.\n\n## Core principles — synthesized across sources\n\n1. **Observed behavior, not interpreted character.** \"You interrupted her twice\" (observable) ≠ \"you're dismissive\" (character judgment).\n2. **Impact over intent.** What actually happened as a result of the behavior, not what the speaker meant.\n3. **Specific and recent.** \"In Wednesday's standup\" beats \"you tend to…\". Recency matters because it's verifiable.\n4. **Future-forward ask.** Every feedback conversation ends with a specific, checkable behavior change.\n5. **Curiosity before conclusion.** Ask what was going on before you announce what went wrong — you may learn something that reframes the whole thing.\n6. **Private, synchronous, voice (not text).** Tough feedback in Slack creates re-reading and escalation.\n\n## Common failure modes\n\n- **Sandwich feedback** (praise → criticism → praise) — well-researched as counterproductive; receivers discount the praise and miss the criticism. Kim Scott, Stone & Heen, and Scott Berkun all recommend dropping it.\n- **Generalizing** — \"you always…\" / \"you never…\". One counterexample and the conversation is over.\n- **Softening to the point of invisibility** — \"it's not a big deal, but…\", \"this is just a small thing…\". The listener concludes it wasn't important and nothing changes.\n- **Ruinous empathy** — withholding because you care. Kim Scott: the kindest thing is often the hardest.\n- **Public delivery** — triggers shame, not learning.\n- **Text delivery** — strips tone, invites worst-case reading.\n- **Ambiguous ask** — \"try to be more collaborative\" is unmeasurable.\n\n## Exemplar phrasings\n\n- **Observable opener**: \"In Wednesday's standup, you interrupted Priya twice while she was explaining the cache issue.\"\n- **Impact**: \"She stopped contributing for the rest of the meeting, and we didn't hear her caching concern until after the decision was made — which we've now had to reopen.\"\n- **Future ask**: \"Going forward, I need you to let whoever is speaking finish before you respond, even if you disagree.\"\n- **Soliciting first**: \"Before I share this, is there anything you'd want *me* to change about how I'm working with you?\"\n- **Curiosity**: \"Help me understand what was happening for you in that moment.\"\n\n## Antipatterns to flag in scoring\n\n- \"I just wanted to say…\"\n- \"This isn't a big deal, but…\"\n- \"Some people feel that…\" (passive voice hiding the speaker)\n- \"You always…\" / \"You never…\"\n- \"I'm only telling you this because I care…\" (doesn't earn what it claims)\n- Skipping the observable behavior and leading with interpretation\n\n## Sources\n\n- Kim Scott, *Radical Candor* (2017); radicalcandor.com (2025)\n- Douglas Stone & Sheila Heen, *Thanks for the Feedback* (2014)\n- Kerry Patterson et al., *Crucial Conversations* (2022 update)\n- Marshall Goldsmith, *What Got You Here Won't Get You There* (2007)\n- Center for Creative Leadership, SBI model (1990s)\n\n## See also\n\n- `bie.md` — Behavior → Impact → Expectation framework for the actual delivery\n- `handling-pressure.md` — the skill dimension stressed hardest in feedback moments\n" }
];

